INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492001, 'A theology should be like poetry, which takes us to the end of what words and thoughts can do.', 4420, 0), (492002, 'Poetry carries its history within it, and it is oral in origin. Its transmission was oral.', 4219, 0), (492003, 'I am an artist, you understand? For me, a picture is like poetry. When you make art, this is not coming from an intellectual place. It''s coming from the deep side of your unconscious, your soul.', 10194, 0), (492004, 'Wanted: a needle swift enough to sew this poem into a blanket.', 2865, 0), (492005, 'I do not see how a man can work on the frontiers of physics and write poetry at the same time. They are in opposition.', 70906, 0), (492006, 'The thing about great poetry is we have no defenses against it.', 19315, 0), (492007, 'I think the poetry that came out of Belfast, and especially the Queen''s University set, in the 1970s and ''80s - you know, Paul Muldoon and Seamus Heaney, Derek Mahon and Ciaran Carson - that was probably the finest body of work since the Gaelic renaissance, up there with the work of Yeats and Synge and Lady Gregory.', 50205, 0), (492008, 'I''m not really a musician. I''m a performer, and I love rock n'' roll. I''ve embraced rock n'' roll because it encompasses all the things I''m interested in: poetry, revolution, sexuality, political activism - all of these things can be found in rock n'' roll.', 1883, 0), (492009, 'I wish our clever young poets would remember my homely definitions of prose and poetry; that is, prose = words in their best order; - poetry = the best words in the best order.', 1910, 0), (492010, 'The poetry of a people comes from the deep recesses of the unconscious, the irrational and the collective body of our ancestral memories.', 1691, 0), (492011, 'Bleak House is just the most astounding piece of work. There''s huge, visionary poetry in it.', 34434, 0), (492012, 'Have you ever heard a good joke? If you''ve ever heard someone just right, with the right pacing, then you''re already on the way to poetry. It''s about using words in very precise ways and using gesture.', 9002, 0), (492013, 'I love Sufism as I love beautiful poetry, but it is not the answer. Sufism is like a mirage in the desert. It says to you, come and sit, relax and enjoy yourself for a while.', 16940, 0), (492014, 'Poetry is the record of the best and happiest moments of the happiest and best minds.', 165, 0), (492015, 'Written poetry is worth reading once, and then should be destroyed. Let the dead poets make way for others.', 9795, 0), (492016, 'Poetry isn''t a profession, it''s a way of life. It''s an empty basket; you put your life into it and make something out of that.', 130, 0), (492017, 'It''s not easy to define poetry.', 289, 0), (492018, 'I don''t like the word ''poetry,'' and I don''t like poetry readings, and I usually don''t like poets. I would much prefer describing myself and what I do as: I''m kind of a curator, and I''m kind of a night-owl reporter.', 2201, 0), (492019, 'I began writing early - very, very early... I was already writing short stories for the radio and selling poems to poetry and art festivals; I was involved in school plays; I wrote essays, so there was no definite moment when I said, ''Now I''m a writer.'' I''ve always been a writer.', 6613, 0), (492020, 'I''ve always written. There''s a journal which I kept from about 9 years old. The man who gave it to me lived across the street from the store and kept it when my grandmother''s papers were destroyed. I''d written some essays. I loved poetry, still do. But I really, really loved it then.', 74, 0), (492021, 'For an American, there''s no automatic place where people love the art of poetry. There''s not a social class that considers poetry its property the way in some countries there''s a snob value to the art.', 8985, 0), (492022, 'If I have to make a self-portrait, I would put poetry and rebellion on the list. To be able to walk on a wire, to be able to juggle six hoops, you need focus, another word for tenacity, which is passion.', 29340, 0), (492023, 'The Victorian language of flowers began with the publication of ''Le Language des Fleurs,'' written by Charlotte de Latour and printed in Paris in 1819. To create the book - which was a list of flowers and their meanings - de Latour gathered references to flower symbolism throughout poetry, ancient mythology, and even medicine.', 2570, 0), (492024, 'I have written some poetry and two prose books about baseball, but if I had been a rich man, I probably would not have written many of the magazine essays that I have had to do. But, needing to write magazine essays to support myself, I looked to things that I cared about and wanted to write about, and certainly baseball was one of them.', 9086, 0), (492025, 'Poetry is one of the ancient arts, and it began as did all the fine arts, within the original wilderness of the earth.', 130, 0), (492026, 'I came into music because I thought the presentation of poetry wasn''t vibrant enough. So I merged improvised poetry with basic rock chords. That was my original mission.', 1883, 0), (492027, 'Like most lit nerds, I''m a voracious reader. I never got enough poetry under my belt growing up but I do read it - some of my favorites, Gina Franco and Angela Shaw and Cornelius Eady and Kevin Young, remind me daily that unless the words sing and dance, what''s the use of putting them down on paper.', 560, 0), (492028, 'Each word bears its weight, so you have to read my poems quite slowly.', 7258, 0), (492029, 'Superstition is the poetry of life.', 282, 0), (492030, 'I started off in England and very few people knew I was Australian. I mean, the clues were in the poems, but they didn''t read them very carefully, and so for years and years I was considered completely part of the English poetry scene.', 58386, 0), (492031, 'The Bible is not just one book, but an entire library, with stories, songs, poetry, letters and history, as well as literature that might more obviously qualify as ''religious.''', 75875, 0), (492032, 'Human beings love poetry. They don''t even know it sometimes... whether they''re the songs of Bono, or the songs of Justin Bieber... they''re listening to poetry.', 74, 0), (492033, 'If the poetry world celebrate its female stars at the true level of their productivity and influence, poetry would wind up being a largely female world, and the men would leave.', 30989, 0), (492034, 'The moment of change is the only poem.', 809, 0), (492035, '''Therefore'' is a word the poet must not know.', 8, 0), (492036, 'Any healthy man can go without food for two days - but not without poetry.', 1165, 0), (492037, 'Poetry is the art of creating imaginary gardens with real toads.', 8786, 0), (492038, 'A poet can survive everything but a misprint.', 40, 0), (492039, 'All bad poetry springs from genuine feeling.', 40, 0), (492040, 'Poetry is ordinary language raised to the Nth power. Poetry is boned with ideas, nerved and blooded with emotions, all held together by the delicate, tough skin of words.', 70214, 0), (492041, 'The crown of literature is poetry.', 235, 0), (492042, 'A poet looks at the world the way a man looks at a woman.', 2547, 0), (492043, 'A poem might be defined as thinking about feelings - about human feelings and frailties.', 7258, 0), (492044, 'He could not die when trees were green, for he loved the time too well.', 8148, 0), (492045, 'There may be more poetry than justice in poetic justice.', 29034, 0), (492046, 'There are men who can write poetry, and there are men who can read balance sheets. The men who can read balance sheets cannot write.', 51914, 0), (492047, 'Poetry is all nouns and verbs.', 8786, 0), (492048, 'The blood jet is poetry and there is no stopping it.', 140, 0), (492049, 'I think that the job of poetry, its political job, is to refresh the idea of justice, which is going dead in us all the time.', 8805, 0), (492050, 'Poetry is a sort of homecoming.', 3840, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492051, 'I didn''t want to deal in poetry. I got rid of that after a few months.', 75876, 0), (492052, 'Of course a poem is a two-way street. No poem is any good if it doesn''t suggest to the reader things from his own mind and recollection that he will read into it, and will add to what the poet has suggested. But I do think poetry readings are very important.', 75877, 0), (492053, 'Pound''s translation of Chinese poetry was maybe the most important thing I read. Eliot a little bit later.', 68479, 0), (492054, 'A group of us started a community center in Santa Monica. We''ve tried different programs, and three have worked really well. A poetry group. Once a week we visit Venice High and talk to girls at risk.', 72796, 0), (492055, 'Slowly poetry becomes visual because it paints images, but it is also musical: it unites two arts into one.', 8779, 0), (492056, 'What we know is that Shakespeare wrote perhaps the most remarkable body of passionate love poetry in the English language to a young man.', 8784, 0), (492057, 'So, poetry becomes a means for useful dialogue between people who are not only unknown, but mute to each other. It produces a dialogue among people that guards all of us against manipulation by our so-called leaders.', 8754, 0), (492058, 'Writing poetry makes you intensely conscious of how words sound, both aloud and inside the head of the reader. You learn the weight of words and how they sound to the ear.', 42138, 0), (492059, 'I want a fever, in poetry: a fever, and tranquillity.', 9013, 0), (492060, 'Why should poetry have to make sense?', 454, 0), (492061, 'The poetry of this one is called philosophical, of that one philological, of a third rhetorical, and so on. Which is then the poetic poetry?', 68443, 0), (492062, 'Yet, it is true, poetry is delicious; the best prose is that which is most full of poetry.', 113, 0), (492063, 'The musician is perhaps the most modest of animals, but he is also the proudest. It is he who invented the sublime art of ruining poetry.', 75878, 0), (492064, 'I see people who talk about America, and then undermine it by not paying attention to its soul, to its poetry. I see polarization, reductionism and superficiality.', 1374, 0), (492065, 'I always wrote poetry and stuff like that, so putting songs together wasn''t that spectacular.', 11891, 0), (492066, 'When I hit a block, regardless of what I am writing, what the subject matter is, or what''s going on in the plot, I go back and I read Pablo Neruda''s poetry. I don''t actually speak Spanish, so I read it translation. But I always go back to Neruda. I don''t know why, but it calms me, calms my brain.', 8095, 0), (492067, 'The middle class is doing fine in fiction. But it''s not what gets me going. I love the working class, and everyone from it I''ve met, and think they''re incredibly witty, inventive - there''s a lot of poetry there.', 228, 0), (492068, 'I read poetry to save time.', 1, 0), (492069, 'The poetry and transgression that was so much of surrealism''s anarchic force has been recruited into mainstream culture. It has been made commonplace by television and magazine merchandising, by computer games and Internet visuals, by film and MTV, by the fashion shoot.', 11876, 0), (492070, 'Modernism in other arts brought extreme difficulty. In poetry, the characteristic difficulty imported under the name of modernism was obscurity. But obscurity could just as easily be a quality of metrical as of free verse.', 4219, 0), (492071, 'Poetry, for me, is the answer to, ''How does one stay sane when private lives are being ransacked by public events?'' It''s something that hangs over your head all the time.', 8840, 0), (492072, 'Poetry is my cheap means of transportation. By the end of the poem the reader should be in a different place from where he started. I would like him to be slightly disoriented at the end, like I drove him outside of town at night and dropped him off in a cornfield.', 8651, 0), (492073, 'I think of something quite different from a snapshot. I know of a lot of poems, some very fine ones, that are like snapshots, but I''m more interested in poetry that is like an endless film, long stories, things that weave together many different strands, like a big piece of cloth, not like a photograph.', 9696, 0), (492074, 'As far as I am concerned, poetry is a statement concerning the human condition, composed in verse.', 10028, 0), (492075, 'My father loved poetry and music. But deep in himself he thought teaching the finest thing a person could do.', 2646, 0), (492076, 'One night, I lay awake for hours, just terrified. When the dawn finally came up - the comfortable blue sky, the familiar world returning - I could think of no other way to express my relief than through poetry. I made a decision there and then that it was what I wanted to do. Every time I pulled a wishbone, it was what I asked for.', 71066, 0), (492077, 'Poetry, fiction as novels or short stories - these are autonomous as created by their authors. They should stand on their own, like pieces of furniture that should be judged as to their usefulness, elegance.', 16120, 0), (492078, 'I am for poetry that is admired by peasant and aristocrat alike.', 16120, 0), (492079, 'For me, I used to be shy towards journalism because it wasn''t poetry. And then I realized that the events that I covered in essays that became journalism were actually great because they inspired me, and they became my muse.', 753, 0), (492080, 'In Northern Ireland, helicopters are not usually used to promote poetry.', 1422, 0), (492081, 'I admire ''Adventure Time'' for being a piece of art in the way that I think art should be. If you want to see it is poetry, you can, and if you don''t, you can watch a fun cartoon.', 75879, 0), (492082, 'When I was young, I read everything I could lay my hands on, but the Scots in my storybooks spent their time fighting glorious battles, rowing across lochs, or escaping over moors of purple heather. Even those Scots were hard to find. For at school, we recited poetry according to the set texts the teachers taught us.', 16256, 0), (492083, 'Surrealism is not a poetry but a poetics, and even more, and more decisively, a world vision.', 8633, 0), (492084, 'Many great works of art, poetry, and music are inspired by astral memories. The desire to do noble, beautiful things here on Earth is also often a carryover of astral experiences between a person''s earth lives.', 2055, 0), (492085, 'I owe my discovery of the Hot Club of Cowtown to Kinky Friedman, leader of the Texas Jewboys. When I saw that Bob Wills and his Texas Playboys were headlining the 2003 Santa Clarita Cowboy Poetry and Music Festival, I thought it my duty to check out the band that had inspired the Texas Jewboys.', 69485, 0), (492086, 'I like cups of tea and reading books and poetry and old people things.', 68250, 0), (492087, 'Poetry is a call to action, and it also is action.', 8822, 0), (492088, 'The muse, the beloved, and duende are three ways of thinking of what is the source of poetry, and all three seem to me different names or different ways to think about something that is not entirely reasonable, not entirely subject to the will, not entirely rational.', 19836, 0), (492089, 'In poetry, I have, since very young, loved poetry in translation. The Chinese, the French, the Russians, Italians, Indians and early Celts: the formality of the translator''s voice, their measured breath and anxiety moves me as it lingers over the original.', 8827, 0), (492090, 'There is a gap in my work from ''84 to 2002, 18 years where I stopped writing. I was working at fiction and other things and starting a school and getting married and starting a family, but I wasn''t writing poetry for the better part of 15 years.', 22390, 0), (492091, 'The major poets of New Jersey have all suffered, whether it''s Whitman, who lost his job for ''Leaves of Grass,'' or William Carlos Williams, who was called a communist, or Ginsberg, whose ''Howl'' was prosecuted, or myself. If you practise poetry the way I think it needs to be done, you''re going to put yourself in jeopardy.', 40810, 0), (492092, 'I do believe that we''ve a responsibility to try to acknowledge the range, both geographic and graphic, of what''s happening in poetry in English. I''m interested in poems that are first-rate. After that, I''m not too concerned if they come from Queens or Queensland.', 71029, 0), (492093, 'When I get depressed, I try to get something for the terrible sadness that comes over me and create something in terms of poetry.', 7873, 0), (492094, 'The applause of his native land is the richest reward to which the patriot ever aspires. It is this for which ''he bears to live or dares to die.'' It is the high incentive to those achievements which illustrate the page of history and give to poetry its brightest charm.', 68667, 0), (492095, 'The topics just kind of come to me. If they are relevant, it''s because they''re happening in the world around me, and it''s affecting me. Poetry is my way of dealing with it.', 694, 0), (492096, 'There is no Frigate like a book to take us lands away nor any coursers like a page of prancing Poetry.', 91, 0), (492097, 'Money is a kind of poetry.', 2547, 0), (492098, 'Music begins to atrophy when it departs too far from the dance... poetry begins to atrophy when it gets too far from music.', 8630, 0), (492099, 'Hence poetry is something more philosophic and of graver import than history, since its statements are rather of the nature of universals, whereas those of history are singulars.', 1116, 0), (492100, 'The Bible should be taught, but emphatically not as reality. It is fiction, myth, poetry, anything but reality. As such it needs to be taught because it underlies so much of our literature and our culture.', 1716, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492101, 'Every now and then I read a poem that does touch something in me, but I never turn to poetry for solace or pleasure in the way that I throw myself into prose.', 28, 0), (492102, 'Verse in itself does not constitute poetry. Verse is only an elegant vestment for a beautiful form. Poetry can express itself in prose, but it does so more perfectly under the grace and majesty of verse. It is poetry of soul that inspires noble sentiments and noble actions as well as noble writings.', 98, 0), (492103, 'I want to promote poetry to the point where you got all the baldhead kids running around doing poetry, getting the music out of the way and having only words, the spoken word, and then see what happens.', 11202, 0), (492104, 'Anybody serious about poetry knows how hard it is to achieve anything worthwhile in it.', 1422, 0), (492105, 'Often people, when they''re confronted with a poem, it''s like someone who keep saying ''what is the meaning of this? What is the meaning of this?'' And that dulls us to the other pleasures poetry offers.', 8651, 0), (492106, 'Radio is such a perfect medium for the transmission of poetry, primarily because there just is the voice, there''s no visual distraction.', 8651, 0), (492107, 'I know my voice has a limited range of motion; I don''t write dramatic monologues and pretend to be other people. But so far, my voice is broad enough to accommodate most of what I want to put into my poetry. I like my persona; I often wish I were him and not me.', 8651, 0), (492108, 'Making poetry with a camera - that''s the essence of what I do.', 69509, 0), (492109, 'Poetry must have something in it that is barbaric, vast and wild.', 2879, 0), (492110, 'Stylized acting and direction is to realistic acting and direction as poetry is to prose.', 64538, 0), (492111, 'Instead of trying to come up and pontificate on what literature is, you need to talk with children, to teachers, and make sure they get poetry in the curriculum early.', 9002, 0), (492112, 'The experience of poetry could bring my mother back to me. Poetry offers a different kind of solace - here on earth.', 8857, 0), (492113, 'I like to borrow forms and quotes and use a lot of allusions, in both poetry and music.', 73214, 0), (492114, 'Sunday is a likely day to write a poem. Because poetry is a piece of language flying around: you''ll find notebooks, something on your phone. It''s about finding them and getting them off that crumpled piece of paper and onto my computer.', 30989, 0), (492115, 'Poetry can tell us about what''s going on in our lives - not only our personal but our social and political lives.', 8822, 0), (492116, 'For this reason poets and artists developed the doctrine of Art for Art''s Sake. The community did not appear to need them, so, tit for tat, they did not need the community. This being granted, it was no longer necessary or even desirable to make one''s poetry either intelligible or sympathetic to the community.', 8656, 0), (492117, 'Good poets have written in order to describe something or to preach something - with their eye on the object or the end. The essence of the poetry does not lie in the thing described or in the message imparted but in the resulting concrete unity, the poem.', 8656, 0), (492118, 'I liked to write from the time I was about 12 or 13. I loved to read. And since I only spoke to my brother, I would write down my thoughts. And I think I wrote some of the worst poetry west of the Rockies. But by the time I was in my 20s, I found myself writing little essays and more poetry - writing at writing.', 74, 0), (492119, 'I wrote some of the worst poetry west from the Mississippi River, but I wrote. And I finally sometimes got it right.', 74, 0), (492120, 'I find in my poetry and prose the rhythms and imagery of the best - I mean, when I''m at my best - of the good Southern black preachers. The lyricism of the spirituals and the directness of gospel songs and the mystery of blues are in my music or in my poetry and prose, or I missed everything.', 74, 0), (492121, 'I''m happy to be a writer - of prose, poetry, every kind of writing. Every person in the world who isn''t a recluse, hermit or mute uses words. I know of no other art form that we always use.', 74, 0), (492122, 'I think that there is nothing, not even crime, more opposed to poetry, to philosophy, ay, to life itself than this incessant business.', 1049, 0), (492123, 'There''s a love of rhetorical skill in the Muslim world. Osama bin Laden doesn''t just go on tape cassettes and say, ''America sucks.'' He recites poetry; he finds things that ''America sucks'' rhymes with.', 10731, 0), (492124, 'It could be that all awful dictators are frustrated artists - Mao with his poetry and Mussolini with his monuments. Stalin was once a journalistic hack, and I can personally testify to how frustrated they are. Pol Pot left a very edgy photo collection behind. And Osama seems quite interested in video.', 10731, 0), (492125, 'I felt like my favorite writers have almost musical hooks in their work, whether it''s poetry or a hook at the end of a chapter that makes you want to read the next one. And I think that my favorite writers definitely have something musical about what they do, in saying something so relatable and universal and so simple.', 100, 0), (492126, 'Poetry and lyrics are very similar. Making words bounce off a page.', 100, 0), (492127, 'We explore our environment, more than we are compelled to utter poetry, when we''re toddlers. We start doing that later. Before that happens, every child is a scientist.', 404, 0), (492128, 'When Auden said his poetry didn''t save one Jew from the gas chamber, he''d said it all.', 408, 0), (492129, 'Science arose from poetry... when times change the two can meet again on a higher level as friends.', 282, 0), (492130, 'You don''t have to be a renowned artist like Q-Tip to try your hand at poetry. You don''t need any special equipment - that''s the beauty of it.', 1997, 0), (492131, 'Poetry has done enough when it charms, but prose must also convince.', 411, 0), (492132, 'The Bible is very resonant. It has everything: creation, betrayal, lust, poetry, prophecy, sacrifice. All great things are in the Bible, and all great writers have drawn from it and more than people realise, whether Shakespeare, Herman Melville or Bob Dylan.', 1883, 0), (492133, 'What I wanted to do in rock ''n roll was merge poetry with sonic scapes, and the two people who had contributed so much to that were Jimi Hendrix and Jim Morrison.', 1883, 0), (492134, 'When I was younger, I felt it was my duty to wake people up. I thought poetry was asleep. I thought rock ''n'' roll was asleep.', 1883, 0), (492135, 'I didn''t love Jim Morrison ''cause he was self-destructive. I loved him because of his work. Because of the way he merged poetry and rock-and-roll. Because he did something new.', 1883, 0), (492136, 'Rhyme, that enslaved queen, that supreme charm of our poetry, that creator of our meter.', 98, 0), (492137, 'In the French language, there is a great gulf between prose and poetry; in English, there is hardly any difference. It is a splendid privilege of the great literary languages Greek, Latin, and French that they possess a prose. English has not this privilege. There is no prose in English.', 98, 0), (492138, 'Writing criticism is to writing fiction and poetry as hugging the shore is to sailing in the open sea.', 135, 0), (492139, 'I must say, when I reread myself, it''s the poetry I tend to look at. It''s the most exciting to write, and it''s over the quickest.', 135, 0), (492140, 'Art works because it appeals to certain faculties of the mind. Music depends on details of the auditory system, painting and sculpture on the visual system. Poetry and literature depend on language.', 3432, 0), (492141, 'The fact that Newark is having poetry festivals and peace conferences - all of these things are building an undeniable thesis that our city is making incredible strides forward.', 10615, 0), (492142, 'On the subject of literary genres, I''ve always felt that my response to poetry is inadequate. I''d love to be the kind of person that drifts off into the garden with a slim volume of Elizabethan verse or a sheaf of haikus, but my passion is story.', 28, 0), (492143, 'As an actor, there is room for a certain amount of creativity, but you''re always ultimately going to be saying somebody else''s words. I don''t think I''d have the stamina, skill or ability to write a novel, but I''d love to write short stories and poetry, because those are my two passions.', 1593, 0), (492144, 'I don''t think I''d have the stamina, skill or ability to write a novel, but I''d love to write short stories and poetry, because those are my two passions.', 1593, 0), (492145, 'On a practical level, poetry isn''t something anybody has really made a great living at. I might sell some books and, once in a while, someone might pay to hear me read.', 2042, 0), (492146, 'Photography, painting or poetry - those are just extensions of me, how I perceive things; they are my way of communicating.', 2042, 0), (492147, 'I have a publishing company of books by me and books of others. It drew people to poetry readings and photo exhibitions and painting exhibitions that I''ve been doing for years before that.', 2042, 0), (492148, 'I''ve been reading poetry publicly for 20 years, and this is what you do - you express, you sometimes dig a bit to get a conversation started. That''s the point of poetry. You''re supposed to go, ''Hmmmm,'' and ''Woooh!''', 70444, 0), (492149, 'I was reading poetry to my girlfriends, and they were like, ''You''re really good. You should go to some poetry readings or something.'' And I eventually went and got a, you know, somewhat of a name for myself and a little bit of a following.', 70444, 0), (492150, 'The claims I''m making for art are simply the claims that we naturally make around music or around poetry. We''re much more relaxed around those art forms. We''re willing to ask, ''How could this find a place in my heart?''', 639, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492151, 'Dylan captured what was on a million minds and turned it into poetry. With ''Blowin'' in the Wind'' or ''The Times They Are A-Changin'','' he set a whole new standard.', 33596, 0), (492152, 'Existential philosophy, poetry and art - just like sadness - were all unavoidable to a tender young man in the meat works.', 10407, 0), (492153, 'When I am writing fiction, I believe I am much better organized, more methodical - one has to be when writing a novel. Writing poetry is a state of free float.', 114, 0), (492154, 'I don''t think of poetry as a ''rational'' activity but as an aural one. My poems usually begin with words or phrases which appeal more because of their sound than their meaning, and the movement and phrasing of a poem are very important to me.', 114, 0), (492155, 'Americans have been tremendously fortunate in poetry, regarding both the quantity and quality of poetry produced. Unfortunately, it remains in schools and universities; it is not widely distributed.', 1254, 0), (492156, 'Poetry is rather an approach to things, to life, than it is typographical production.', 1254, 0), (492157, 'Poetry seems to be the only weapon able to beat language, using language''s own means.', 1254, 0), (492158, 'To translate poetry, one has to possess some art, at the very least the art of stylistic re-embodiment.', 1254, 0), (492159, 'The more one reads poetry, the less tolerant one becomes of any sort of verbosity, be that in political or philosophical discourse, be that in history, social studies or the art of fiction.', 1254, 0), (492160, 'My idea is simply - is very simple - is that the books of poetry should be published in far greater volume and be distributed in far greater volume, in far more substantial manner. You can sell in supermarkets very cheaply. In paperbacks. You can sell in drugstores.', 1254, 0), (492161, 'This assumption that the blue collar crowd is not supposed to read it, or a farmer in his overalls is not to read poetry, seems to be dangerous if not tragic.', 1254, 0), (492162, 'I am a patriot, but I must say that English poetry is the richest in the world.', 1254, 0), (492163, 'Poetry is not an art or a branch of art: it''s something more.', 1254, 0), (492164, 'Anyone who regards poetry as an entertainment, as a ''read,'' commits an anthropological crime, in the first place against himself.', 1254, 0), (492165, 'American poetry to me is a sort of relentless, nonstop sermon on human autonomy.', 1254, 0), (492166, 'Tyranny will make an entire population into readers of poetry.', 1254, 0), (492167, 'American poetry is this country''s greatest patrimony. It takes a stranger to see some things clearly. This is one of them, and I am that stranger.', 1254, 0), (492168, 'Poetry isn''t just different from prose, it''s more important for the human species.', 1254, 0), (492169, 'The charge frequently leveled against poetry - that it is difficult, obscure, hermetic and whatnot - indicates not the state of poetry but, frankly, the rung of the evolutionary ladder on which society is stuck.', 1254, 0), (492170, 'People who buy ''The National Enquirer'' would buy poetry. They should be given a choice. I''m absolutely serious.', 1254, 0), (492171, 'People compose poetry, novels, sitcoms - for love.', 52746, 0), (492172, 'Being able to say something lyrically, to say something that will do more than just be words, is really hard. It''s easy to do when you''re writing a chapter of a book or writing poetry, but it''s really hard to do when you''re confined to a melody line.', 1197, 0), (492173, 'That metre itself forms an essential part of all true poetry is a principle which not even the assertions of an Aristotle or the pronouncements of a Plato can disestablish.', 1060, 0), (492174, 'When you are writing literary writing, you are communicating something subtextual with emotions and poetry. The prose has to have a voice; it''s not just typing. It takes a while to get that voice.', 852, 0), (492175, 'I''m moved by people who see the world differently than others. People who see the world with a longing for its poetry often can be broken people.', 68913, 0), (492176, 'For awhile after you quit Keats all other poetry seems to be only whistling or humming.', 97, 0), (492177, 'What is beautiful enchants me. I mean not just physical beauty but a wider concept of beauty. There is beauty in poetry and in great musical or singing performances. There is beauty everywhere if you can just see it.', 67812, 0), (492178, 'Personally I always feel like I could use a little more of poetry apothegmatic power in my own work but we''re always lacking something.', 560, 0), (492179, 'I didn''t start writing songs, honestly, until I started making my album. I was always doing poetry, but I never thought I could write songs. I discouraged myself and thought it was so hard. But starting this process and learning just what it is to be a songwriter and performer taught me that you don''t have to feel discouraged about anything.', 68914, 0), (492180, 'In much of computer science, I can easily ''auto-grade'' your work and give you an instant meaningful feedback. I can''t do this when it comes to the subtlety of human thought, language, poetry, philosophy.', 66947, 0), (492181, 'I want to branch out. I want to write. I write poetry. I want to see my children grow up well.', 22705, 0), (492182, 'Poetry is all that is worth remembering in life.', 8948, 0), (492183, 'Shakespeare is rhythmic; he is musical in the sense that he likes poetry, and he''s musical because he constantly refers to settings where there''s singing and dancing.', 63679, 0), (492184, 'Maybe it is something to do with age, but I have become fonder of poetry than of prose.', 5358, 0), (492185, 'I love reading poetry, and yet, at this point, the thought of writing a poem, to me, is tantamount to figuring out a trigonometry question.', 1590, 0), (492186, 'It''s just poetry, beauty and love. How hard can that be to act?', 70666, 0), (492187, 'I certainly derived my skills as a prose writer from my scrutiny of poetry and of the individual word. But schools don''t do things like that anymore - tracking words down to their roots.', 1920, 0), (492188, 'When the poet is in love, he is incapable of writing poetry on love. He has to write when he remembers that he was in love.', 736, 0), (492189, 'I have felt great advances in my poetry, the main one being a growing victory over word nuances and a superfluity of adjectives.', 140, 0), (492190, 'Well, I still write poetry, but I wouldn''t call myself a poet.', 54756, 0), (492191, 'Well you can''t teach the poetry, but you can teach the craft.', 69898, 0), (492192, 'I went through a phase of reading lots of Urdu poetry, thanks to the great transliterated versions that have become available.', 54622, 0), (492193, 'No poems can please for long or live that are written by water drinkers.', 2542, 0), (492194, 'The greatest thing a human soul ever does in this world... to see clearly is poetry, prophecy and religion all in one.', 485, 0), (492195, 'There''s poetry in being the band that can sell out Wembley but also makes a record in a garage. I don''t like doing what people expect me to do.', 22301, 0), (492196, 'I''ve read a lot of war writing, even World War I writing, the British war poetry of Wilfred Owen and Siegfried Sassoon, Robert Graves''s memoir ''Goodbye to All That,'' and a civilian memoir, ''Testament of Youth,'' by Vera Brittain.', 14528, 0), (492197, 'You pick up loads of baggage with your first record with reaction to it from fans and critics. So I went to Ireland by myself for a couple of weeks with my guitar. I read lots of poetry, I read Patti Smith''s autobiography and started words and phrases and then songs started to take shape.', 16756, 0), (492198, 'When I was in college, I really liked poetry. I don''t read much anymore.', 748, 0), (492199, 'I want to write a play. I''d like to do an original musical. I should probably put together a poetry collection.', 14, 0), (492200, 'We are supposed to write poetry to keep the gods alive.', 2687, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492201, 'I think poetry is able to say things in such a small, perfect way that are so hard to say. I think it''s a perfect medium for expressing difficult ideas and concepts and feelings. It''s one of my great loves.', 65023, 0), (492202, 'I find a lot of poetry to be narcissistic.', 16696, 0), (492203, 'Poetry consists in a rhyming dictionary and things seen.', 1267, 0), (492204, 'Poetry has, in a way, been my bridge to my acting career.', 69322, 0), (492205, 'I found poetry at 12 and 13 and, lo and behold, learned that my attorney father had a background in poetry - as he wore dashikis and Afros in the ''70s and named his kids Arabic names. He was a poet and a lot like The Last Poets and Gil Scott-Heron and all of these folks. He definitely was an artist.', 69322, 0), (492206, 'I was trying to pay the bills with poems, and it was easy to memorize my poems, because I''d be riding my bike in California trying to memorize them before going on stage at a poetry lounge.', 69322, 0), (492207, 'That''s the thing with me being a former athlete: in the way I attack characters and attack poetry is from the base of being an athlete.', 69322, 0), (492208, 'Poetry is almost like my foundation for everything. I almost feel I am a better actor and writer because of it.', 69322, 0), (492209, 'The fact of the matter is that the most unexpected and miraculous thing in my life was the arrival in it of poetry itself - as a vocation and an elevation almost.', 1422, 0), (492210, 'Nowadays, what an award gives is a sense of solidarity with the poetry guild, as it were: sustenance coming from the assent of your peers on the judging panel.', 1422, 0), (492211, 'I credit poetry for making this space-walk possible.', 1422, 0), (492212, 'Manifesting that order of poetry where we can at last grow up to that which we stored up as we grew.', 1422, 0), (492213, 'Dylan Thomas is now as much a case history as a chapter in the history of poetry.', 1422, 0), (492214, 'A public expectation, it has to be said, not of poetry as such but of political positions variously approvable by mutually disapproving groups.', 1422, 0), (492215, 'The completely solitary self: that''s where poetry comes from, and it gets isolated by crisis, and those crises are often very intimate also.', 1422, 0), (492216, 'Poetry is always slightly mysterious, and you wonder what is your relationship to it.', 1422, 0), (492217, 'The experimental poetry thing is not my thing. It''s a programme of the avant-garde: basically a refusal of the kind of poetry I write.', 1422, 0), (492218, 'The experiment of poetry, as far as I am concerned, happens when the poem carries you beyond where you could have reasonably expected to go.', 1422, 0), (492219, 'In the United States, in poetry workshops, it''s now quite a thing to make graduate students learn poems by heart.', 1422, 0), (492220, 'In poetry, everything can be faked but the intensity of utterance.', 1422, 0), (492221, 'Tom Sleigh''s poetry is hard-earned and well founded. I great admire the way it refuses to cut emotional corners and yet achieves a sense of lyric absolution.', 1422, 0), (492222, 'Poetry is a domestic art, most itself when most at home.', 1422, 0), (492223, 'Poetry is more a threshold than a path.', 1422, 0), (492224, 'A play is basically a long, formalistic polemic. You can write it without the poetry, and if you do, you may have a pretty good play. We know this because we see plays in translation. Not many people speak Norwegian or Danish or whatever guys like Ibsen spoke, or Russian - yet we understand Chekhov and the others.', 2221, 0), (492225, 'It''s always a combination of physics and poetry that I find inspiring. It''s hard to wrap your head around things like the Hubble scope.', 13172, 0), (492226, 'There isn''t, even now, a great tradition of novel-writing in Afghanistan. Most of the literature is in the form of poetry.', 342, 0), (492227, 'I learn poetry, learn text, and that really keeps you alive.', 48587, 0), (492228, 'Metaphorical tone deafness is when people are unable to discern what is of value in something. I think I''m tone deaf to poetry, for instance. Despite having studied it into a second year of university, most of it just leaves me cold.', 67531, 0), (492229, 'It would probably surprise people to know that I''m interested in wildlife. I read a lot of poetry, too.', 68437, 0), (492230, 'Poetry and progress are like two ambitious men who hate one another with an instinctive hatred, and when they meet upon the same road, one of them has to give place.', 1165, 0), (492231, 'France is not poetic; she even feels, in fact, a congenital horror of poetry. Among the writers who use verse, those whom she will always prefer are the most prosaic.', 1165, 0), (492232, 'In traditional Asian arts, the word and the picture always sit next to each other. I have an aunt, a Chinese brush painter, who told me that when you do a Chinese brush painting, you have to pair the image up with some poetry.', 16732, 0), (492233, 'Whether you like modern incarnations of what country radio hits are, or you like what I''m doing, or you like something really off in folk, poetry Americana land, it''s all just music, man. If you like one of them, great - go buy it.', 66588, 0), (492234, 'So now I have a collection of poetry by Aaron Neville and I give it to people I want to share it with. I''d like to publish it someday.', 67027, 0), (492235, 'I write poetry on my iPhone. I''ve got about 100 poems on there.', 67027, 0), (492236, 'It''s more fun to have a name rather than a number. I think this gives our products a personality. I get the names from literature, movies, opera, traveling, nature, poetry, sometimes even the street. I keep a small book that I write in. I wake up in the middle of the night and jot down a name for a lipstick or an eyeshadow.', 70668, 0), (492237, 'Magna Carta has become totemic. It is in the comedy of Tony Hancock, in the poetry of Kipling, never far from the front pages in a constitutional crisis.', 67032, 0), (492238, 'I think poetry is a fabulous medium to encapsulate thoughts far more precisely than prose.', 69732, 0), (492239, 'I was writing poetry, and the Mountain Goats was an outgrowth of that.', 16432, 0), (492240, 'Opera combines pretty basic theater and poetry, but the storyline itself is actually quite poetic and, after some digital research, taking that actual content and seeing it as undeniably poetic.', 16432, 0), (492241, 'My father would tell me if I wasn''t writing in meter verse, it wasn''t poetry.', 16432, 0), (492242, 'I do think digital media encourages speed-reading, which can be fine if one is simply seeking information. But a serious novel or work of history or volume of poetry is an experience one should savor, take time over.', 14168, 0), (492243, 'Most lyric poetry is about love, whether yearned after, fulfilled, or wistfully regretted; what isn''t tends to consist of laments and cris du coeur over this, that, and the other.', 14168, 0), (492244, 'It''s something we, guys, have all done. Made tapes for girls, trying to impress them, to meet them on a shared plane of aesthetics. Read them someone else''s poetry because they do poetry better than you could do it, because you''re too awkward to do it.', 70232, 0), (492245, 'Muhammadan law in its relation to women, is a pattern to European law. Look back to the history of Islam, and you will find that women have often taken leading places - on the throne, in the battle-field, in politics, in literature, poetry, etc.', 4208, 0), (492246, 'I never really liked poetry readings; I liked to read poetry by myself, but I liked singing, chanting my lyrics to this jazz group.', 571, 0), (492247, 'I always thought that poetry is the verdict that others give to a certain kind of writing. So to call yourself a poet is a kind of dangerous description. It''s for others it''s for others to use. ', 571, 0), (492248, 'I have written about some truly great writers - John Steinbeck, Robert Frost, and William Faulkner. Faulkner and Frost were the very peaks of American poetry and fiction in the 20th century.', 50301, 0), (492249, 'I think of it this way: When you hear that people have downloaded your comic, appreciate that thousands are eager to hear what you have to say. The poetry club down the hall may not have the same problem. That''s a good problem to have.', 2654, 0), (492250, 'Poetry stands or falls by its music.', 12852, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492251, 'My poems tend to be more celebratory and lyrical, and the novels so far pretty dark. Poetry doesn''t seem to me to be an appropriate tool for exploring that.', 12852, 0), (492252, 'With fiction, I tend to get to my desk and start writing. Poetry I write in my head, often while walking, so that my poems have an organic quality, hopefully.', 12852, 0), (492253, 'I realised I''d spent a lot of time in my poetry trying to find a way of talking about that whereof we cannot speak.', 12852, 0), (492254, 'I was a 16-year-old girl at one point, so of course I wrote poetry.', 18433, 0), (492255, 'I was born in a world of opera, theatre, films, poetry, art, and therefore, out of the wire, I made a stage. That''s why they call me a high wire artist.', 29340, 0), (492256, 'I was always interested in French poetry sort of as a sideline to my own work, I was translating contemporary French poets. That kind of spilled out into translation as a way to earn money, pay for food and put bread on the table.', 496, 0), (492257, 'I started out in life as a poet; I was only writing poetry all through my 20s. It wasn''t until I was about 30 that I got serious about writing prose. While I was writing poems, I would often divert myself by reading detective novels; I liked them.', 496, 0), (492258, 'Every American poet feels that the whole responsibility for contemporary poetry has fallen upon his shoulders, that he is a literary aristocracy of one.', 219, 0), (492259, 'I think when kids just see well-crafted poetry, it''s just obtuse to them. It''s hard to relate to.', 7655, 0), (492260, 'I''ve always had a love for poetry and when I got signed to a record label I thought, ''How odd that I''m doing a record before a book of poetry,''', 7655, 0), (492261, 'Poetry. I read Walt Whitman, Emily Dickinson, and Jane Hirschfield. I like to read Billy Collins out loud.', 1039, 0), (492262, 'When you act, you''ve got to be like a poet or a musician. It''s not about evidence before court. It''s not a forensic subject. It''s poetry; it''s a completely different place.', 68873, 0), (492263, 'You know, bad poetry I wrote in high school can still be found on the Internet, and, you know, there''s a Web log of our college newspaper. You know, there''s so many different stages of my creative development are sort of on-record if somebody were to choose to look for them.', 2250, 0), (492264, 'I have written some songs, but I would really call what I''ve done poetry at the end of the day, because I''ll sit with my guitar for hours and hours on end for, like, a week and then I won''t touch it for a month. I also just have no confidence. And you know what? I don''t have time, because I''d rather be doing other things, like knitting.', 69265, 0), (492265, 'I''m moving to Rio permanently with my family. It''s one of the places left in the world where people still live with a big charge of poetry on a daily basis. I feel we''ve kind of lost that here in Europe.', 74289, 0), (492266, 'Every single soul is a poem.', 21674, 0), (492267, 'A poem is true if it hangs together. Information points to something else. A poem points to nothing but itself.', 102, 0), (492268, 'The sort of poetry I seek resides in objects man can''t touch.', 102, 0), (492269, 'A definition of poetry can only determine what poetry should be and not what poetry actually was and is otherwise the most concise formula would be: Poetry is that which at some time and some place was thus named. ', 68443, 0), (492270, 'One has only as much morality as one has philosophy and poetry.', 68443, 0), (492271, 'Women are treated as unjustly in poetry as in life. The feminine ones are not idealistic, and the idealistic not feminine.', 68443, 0), (492272, 'From what the moderns want, we must learn what poetry should become; from what the ancients did, what poetry must be.', 68443, 0), (492273, 'Women do not have as great a need for poetry because their own essence is poetry.', 68443, 0), (492274, 'Nothing truly convincing - which would possess thoroughness, vigor, and skill - has been written against the ancients as yet; especially not against their poetry.', 68443, 0), (492275, 'If you want to see mankind fully, look at a family. Within the family minds become organically one, and for this reason the family is total poetry.', 68443, 0), (492276, 'A connection between poetry and blindness is a classical trope.', 30978, 0), (492277, 'I used to spend a lot of time dreaming and writing poetry.', 67868, 0), (492278, 'I think if a poet wanted to lead, he or she would want the message to be unequivocally clear and free of ambiguity. Whereas poetry is actually the home of ambiguity, ambivalence and uncertainty.', 8651, 0), (492279, 'In the long revolt against inherited forms that has by now become the narrative of 20th-century poetry in English, no poet was more flamboyant or more recognizable in his iconoclasm than Cummings.', 8651, 0), (492280, 'There are interesting forms of difficulty, and there are unprofitable forms of difficulty. I mean, I enjoy some difficult poetry, but some of it is impenetrable and I actually wouldn''t want to penetrate it if I could, perhaps.', 8651, 0), (492281, 'Listeners are kind of ambushed... if a poem just happens to be said when they''re listening to the radio. The listener doesn''t have time to deploy what I call their ''poetry deflector shields'' that were installed in high school - there''s little time to resist the poem.', 8651, 0), (492282, 'I''m pretty much all for poetry in public places - poetry on buses, poetry on subways, on billboards, on cereal boxes.', 8651, 0), (492283, 'We love, you know, children love the ingredients of poetry. And then they go into this tunnel that we call adolescence, and when they come out of it, they hate poetry.', 8651, 0), (492284, 'I have my Poetry 180 project, which I''ve made my main project. We encourage high schools, because that''s really where, for most people, poetry dies off and gets buried under other adolescent pursuits.', 8651, 0), (492285, 'I don''t think anybody reads a book of poetry front to back. Editors and reviewers only. I don''t think anybody else does.', 8651, 0), (492286, 'When I was a young man, I understood that poetry was two things - it was difficult to understand, but you could understand that the poet was miserable. So for a while there, I wrote poems that were hard to understand, even by me, but gave off whiffs of misery.', 8651, 0), (492287, 'When I became poet laureate, I was in a slightly uncomfortable position because I think a lot of poetry isn''t worth reading.', 8651, 0), (492288, 'For most Americans, poetry plays no role in their everyday lives. But also for most Americans, contemporary painting or jazz or sculpture play no role either. I''m not saying poetry is singled out as a special thing to ignore.', 8651, 0), (492289, 'People think of poetry as a school subject... Poetry is very frustrating to students because they don''t have a taste for ambiguity, for one thing. That gives them a poetry hangover.', 8651, 0), (492290, 'My persona is less miserable than a lot of contemporary poetry speakers are.', 8651, 0), (492291, 'I''m all for poetry catching up with technology, and just as there are iTunes, I think we should have iPoems. I mean, people should be able to walk around with their earbuds in and listening to poems on their iPod.', 8651, 0), (492292, 'I find a lot of poetry very disappointing, but I do have poets that I go back to. One book of poetry that I''d like to mention is ''The Exchange'' by Sophie Cabot Black. Her poems are difficult without being too difficult.', 8651, 0), (492293, 'Some honor Cummings as the granddaddy of all American innovators in poetry and ascribe to him a diverse progeny that includes virtually any poet who considers the page a field and allows silence to be part of poetry''s expressiveness.', 8651, 0), (492294, 'Few rappers realize the genre sprang from West African griots through Delta slave songs to jazz poetry and the comedic trash talk of ''the dozens.''', 28763, 0), (492295, 'I always wrote poetry as a teenager and it was always so dark, but it made me feel good to get it out.', 67650, 0), (492296, 'I like poetry when I don''t quite understand why I like it. Poetry isn''t just a question of wrapping something up and giving it to someone else to unwrap. It just doesn''t work like that.', 1066, 0), (492297, 'I like to write poetry.', 72578, 0), (492298, 'I wrote things for the school''s newspaper, and - like all teenagers - I dabbled in poetry.', 1450, 0), (492299, 'You know that thing people say, ''poetry is the hardest, stories are the second hardest, novels are the easiest?'' I''m here to tell you that novels are the hardest. Writing a novel is unbelievably difficult. It''s nightmarish.', 31136, 0), (492300, 'I love the simple poetry of theater, where you can stand in a spotlight on a stage and wrap a coat around you, and say, ''It was 1860 and it was winter...''', 3625, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492301, 'You don''t have to live in a garage to write great poetry.', 67811, 0), (492302, 'I want to prove that if you write in strict meter and rhyme about subjects people care about, they will buy poetry.', 67811, 0), (492303, 'I am absolutely convinced that my life was redeemed by poetry.', 67811, 0), (492304, 'With a poetry book I can send 100 copies out to reviewers and other people, and even do it in advance and get their response. It''s difficult with iPad: how do you send it out for free, and how do you even disseminate it before it goes into their store?', 67811, 0), (492305, 'Poetry is one of the oldest of all art forms, and one of its powers for shamans and tribal leaders was the mnemonic.', 67811, 0), (492306, 'Poetry is the experience of liberty. The poet risks himself, chances all on the poem''s all with each verse he writes.', 8633, 0), (492307, 'Poetry is not a genre in harmony with the modern world; its innermost nature is hostile or indifferent to the dogmas of modern times, progress and the cult of the future.', 8633, 0), (492308, 'Poetry, whatever the manifest content of the poem, is always a violation of the rationalism and morality of bourgeois society.', 8633, 0), (492309, 'Any reflection about poetry should begin, or end, with this question: who and how many read poetry books?', 8633, 0), (492310, 'I''ve written for every medium except poetry, at which I suck.', 3183, 0), (492311, 'Poetry is not an issue of form and enjambments. Poetry, as the word is classically used, has to do with sound and sense. It can be rhyme. It can be rhythm, pace, breath.', 3159, 0), (492312, 'Sufi poetry is, in a sense, self-help poetry about how to live a decent life, how to deal with your mortality.', 5980, 0), (492313, 'Sylvia Plath, Rumi, there''s a lot of spoken word poets who do a really incredible job putting their spoken work into page poetry - that''s what I strive to do.', 67060, 0), (492314, 'There is no real way to categorize McLean''s ''American Pie'' for its hybrid of modern poetry and folk ballad, beer-hall chant and high-art rock.', 19715, 0), (492315, 'That''s all there was in our house: poetry and choir rehearsal and duets and so forth I listened to Dad and Mother discuss things about poetry and delivery and voice and diction - I don''t think anyone could know how much it really means. ', 67724, 0), (492316, 'My dad was the cause of me being in show business. He was not only in poetry but in acting a bit. He was Mordecai in the play ''A Dream of Queen Esther.''', 67724, 0), (492317, 'I love poetry. I love rhyming. Do you know, there are poets who don''t rhyme? Shakespeare did not rhyme most of the time, and that''s why I do not like him.', 67724, 0), (492318, 'All I knew about Ethiopia was from a few records that I like, as well as what I read about the famine. But you get there and it''s another world. It''s filled with art and music and poetry and intellectuals and writers - all kinds of people.', 71038, 0), (492319, 'My dad is a Jack Nicholson lookalike and a frustrated performer, my mother''s into reading and poetry. I suppose the thing I owe them most is my confidence.', 69745, 0), (492320, 'For thousands of years, poetry has been picturing love as a mysterious and tragic power. But when anyone says the same thing in plain prose, and adds that life would be colourless and poor without the great passions, then this is called immorality!', 62381, 0), (492321, 'When the modern movement began, starting perhaps with the paintings of Manet and the poetry of Baudelaire and Rimbaud, what distinguished the modern movement was the enormous honesty that writers, painters and playwrights displayed about themselves. The bourgeois novel flinches from such notions.', 2312, 0), (492322, 'Poetry is what we turn to in the most emotional moments of our life - when a beloved friend dies, when a baby is born or when we fall in love.', 405, 0), (492323, 'Poetry is the language we speak in the most terrifying or ecstatic passages of our lives. But the very word poetry scares people. They think of their grade school teachers reciting ''Hiawatha'' and they groan.', 405, 0), (492324, 'I guess the thing that I''m most proud of is that I kept on writing poetry. I understand that poetry is sort of the source of everything I do. It''s the source of my creativity.', 405, 0), (492325, 'I thought to spend my declining years writing poetry and teaching - but that won''t pay the Bergdorf''s bill. I think I''ll move to somewhere life is cheaper.', 405, 0), (492326, 'Often I find that poems predict what I''m going to do later in my own writing, and often I find that poems predict my life. So I think poetry is the most intense expression of feeling that we have.', 405, 0), (492327, 'In poetry you can express almost inexpressible feelings. You can express the pain of loss, you can express love. People always turn to poetry when someone they love dies, when they fall in love.', 405, 0), (492328, 'I can''t understand Urdu, Bahasa or Russian, but when the Pakistani Faiz, the Indonesian Rendra and the Russian Rosdentvensky declaim, I can feel the living throb of rhythm and music, the warmth and passion of their poetry, as do the hundreds, not a mere roomful, of poetry lovers in the audience.', 16120, 0), (492329, 'We read Robert Browning''s poetry. Here we needed no guidance from the professor: the poems themselves were enough.', 1301, 0), (492330, 'When I was writing pretty poor poetry, this girl with midnight black hair told me to go on.', 1301, 0), (492331, 'Poetry is a phantom script telling how rainbows are made and why they go away.', 1301, 0), (492332, 'My work should be seen as poetry.', 70243, 0), (492333, 'The commitment to working at poetry is important because a poet is a maker, and a poem is a made thing. We have to honor our feelings by working to transform them into something meaningful and lasting.', 19836, 0), (492334, 'I''m a poet, and I spent my life in poetry.', 19836, 0), (492335, 'Someone who''s awake in the middle of the night is a soul consciousness when everyone else is asleep, and that creates a feeling of solitude in poetry that I very much like.', 19836, 0), (492336, 'You''re shadowed by your own dream, especially as you get older, of trying to create something that will last in poetry. And so, you''re working on its behalf.', 19836, 0), (492337, 'There have always been great defenses of poetry, and I''ve tried to write mine, and I think all of my work and criticism is a defense of poetry to try and keep something alive in poetry.', 19836, 0), (492338, 'When I taught at the University of Houston in the Creative Writing program, we required the poets to take workshops in fiction writing, and we required the fiction writers to take workshops in poetry.', 19836, 0), (492339, 'I don''t think you can read poetry while you''re watching television very well.', 19836, 0), (492340, 'The idea of how to read a poem is based on the idea that poetry needs you as a reader. That the experience of poetry, the meaning in poetry, is a kind of circuit that takes place between a poet, a poem and a reader, and that meaning doesn''t exist or inhere in poems alone.', 19836, 0), (492341, 'There''s never been a culture without poetry in the history of the world.', 19836, 0), (492342, 'In every culture, in every language, there is expressive play, expressive word play; there''s language use to different purposes that we would call poetry.', 19836, 0), (492343, 'I don''t think poetry will die, but I think that poetry does demand a certain kind of attention to language. It does demand a certain space in order to read it, and I think that space is somewhat threatened by the lack of attention that people have and the amount of time that they give to things.', 19836, 0), (492344, 'I had feelings that I didn''t know what to do with, and I felt better when I started writing them. I thought of it as poetry. I did notice girls really liked it. Better than football. They liked the combination.', 19836, 0), (492345, 'I''d say people do need some help with poetry because I think poetry just helps takes us to places that Americans aren''t always accustomed to going.', 19836, 0), (492346, 'I find great consolation in having a lot of poetry books around. I believe that writing poetry and reading it are deeply intertwined. I''ve always delighted in the company of the poets I''ve read.', 19836, 0), (492347, 'As long as there''s been poetry, there have been lamentations.', 19836, 0), (492348, 'Poetry is a form of necessary speech... I have sought to restore the aura of sacred practice that accompanies true poetic creation, to honor both the rational and the irrational elements of poetry.', 19836, 0), (492349, 'Poetry is meant to inspire readers and listeners, to connect them more deeply to themselves even as it links them more fully to others. But many people feel put off by the terms of poetry, its odd vocabulary, its notorious difficulty.', 19836, 0), (492350, 'The terms of poetry - some simple, some complicated, some ancient, some new - should bring us closer to what we''re hearing, enlarging our experience of it, enabling us to describe what we''re reading, to feel and think with greater precision.', 19836, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492351, 'The line is a way of framing poetry. All verse is measured by lines. The poetic line immediately announces its difference from everyday speech and prose.', 19836, 0), (492352, 'The sense of flowing, which is so crucial to song, is also crucial to poetry.', 19836, 0), (492353, 'When poetry separates from song, then the words have to carry all the rhythm themselves; they have to do all the work. They can''t rely on the singing voice.', 19836, 0), (492354, 'One of the things that distinguishes poetry from ordinary speech is that in a very few number of words, poetry captures some kind of deep feeling, and rhythm is the way to get there. Rhythm is the way the poetry carries itself.', 19836, 0), (492355, 'I started writing poetry as a teenager in suburban Chicago out of emotional desperation.', 19836, 0), (492356, 'I grew up in a middle-class house without books, without art. No one around me wrote poetry or even read it.', 19836, 0), (492357, 'Poetry itself hasn''t been well served by poets who fled to the margins.', 19836, 0), (492358, 'I aspire to a poetry of great formal integrity, deep passion and high intellect, and I have many models for how to do that.', 19836, 0), (492359, 'I''m so happy to be an advocate for poetry.', 19836, 0), (492360, 'I didn''t read poetry seriously until college, when I really began to devour it in a very intense way. I also discovered that a poet is a maker. Before that, I thought a poet was someone who wrote about his own experiences.', 19836, 0), (492361, 'The idea that a poem was a made thing stayed with me, and I decided then that I wanted to be an artist, not just a diarist. So I put myself through a kind of apprenticeship in writing poetry, and I understood even then that my practice as a poet was deeply related to my reading.', 19836, 0), (492362, 'Poetry is a vocation. It is not a career but a calling.', 19836, 0), (492363, 'Writing poetry is such an intense experience that it helps to start the process in a casual or wayward frame of mind.', 19836, 0), (492364, 'Poetry takes place in time. It is a durational. Things take place in sequence.', 19836, 0), (492365, 'Poetry, being supremely useless, by its very existence represents a protest against the so-called ''real world'' of busy-ness and moneymaking, so we must embrace, salute and support our poets.', 16461, 0), (492366, 'I didn''t start off as a journalist; I started off as a poet. My ambition was to practise poetry. Then I found journalism, but that other voice never fled from me.', 1309, 0), (492367, 'One thing I do know is that poetry, to be understood, must be clear.', 130, 0), (492368, 'People want poetry. They need poetry. They get it. They don''t want fancy work.', 130, 0), (492369, 'Poetry is meant to be heard.', 130, 0), (492370, 'You know, in my music career there was a moment where the irony was just so heavy. There were people in my audience that were the reason I developed neuroses. These people that tortured my life were using my art, my poetry, as fuel for them, to torture other people.', 69263, 0), (492371, 'I really enjoy English and poetry and writing classes.', 72570, 0), (492372, 'All one''s inventions are true, you can be sure of that. Poetry is as exact a science as geometry.', 647, 0), (492373, 'Poetry is something to make us wiser and better, by continually revealing those types of beauty and truth, which God has set in all men''s souls.', 1247, 0), (492374, 'As the years pass, I find that writers who were once central to me aren''t anymore. I revered Yeats''s poetry in college. I respect it now and am still ravished by certain lines, but I don''t go back to him again and again. I do go back to Emily Dickinson again and again.', 68863, 0), (492375, 'Popular music is one endless love song that, I suspect, the basically solitary Ella Fitzgerald approached much as the basically solitary Marianne Moore approached poetry: reading it with a certain contempt for it, Moore said, you could find a place in it for the genuine.', 68863, 0), (492376, 'Fiction is supposed to be immersive and supposed to be entertaining and narrative, so structures have to be buried a little bit. If they come foregrounded too much, it stops being fiction and starts being poetry - something more concrete and out of time.', 229, 0), (492377, 'Poetry was one of the things that interested me most as I was growing up. I used to write it in my head all the time. I still think the very greatest pleasure in life is to write a poem.', 30169, 0), (492378, '''Words and Music'' on Radio 3 is always a treat. Actors read passages of poetry and prose interspersed with music, and nobody tells you what it is. Later you can look it up online, but at the time you can''t cheat.', 30169, 0), (492379, 'I read usually in the morning, in my kitchen at breakfast - a short reading time, usually poetry. I read in bed every night. I usually get in bed pretty early with a book, and I read until I can''t prop my eyes open anymore - sometimes rather late.', 723, 0), (492380, 'Country music especially can get very formulaic - you know, you have to have your verses and a bridge and a chorus, and a lot of the songs are written as just plain and simple poetry on the road.', 74285, 0), (492381, 'Poetry is the hardest thing that there is. It fascinates me, so I want to write more of it.', 55413, 0), (492382, 'Gregory Corso used to get really pissed when people called Bob Dylan a ''poet.'' After writing poetry for a few years, I can understand that.', 55413, 0), (492383, 'Becoming interested in poetics got me interested in theater. Theater is supposed to be poetry, you know, before it''s anything else. It just doesn''t fly if it isn''t musical.', 55413, 0), (492384, 'I wrote poetry, which got me into lyrics. Stevie Wonder, Carole King, Elton John pulled me into pop. I started singing with a band - just for fun - when I was 17. And pretty soon, I was thinking I could sing pop in English as well as Spanish.', 64979, 0), (492385, 'Is there any purpose to translating poetry? A poem does not contain information of importance, like a signpost or a warning notice.', 68800, 0), (492386, 'I used to buy scented poetry books on tour and read aloud to the band. Not what you''d expect, huh?', 67772, 0), (492387, 'There was no market for poetry about trauma, abuse, loss, love, and healing through the lens of a Punjabi-Sikh immigrant woman.', 694, 0), (492388, 'I would give anything to sing like Beyonce or Adele. I''ve said many times to my friends that if I could sing like them, I would give up poetry and writing.', 694, 0), (492389, 'Poetry and art are key influences in changing how we look at taboos.', 694, 0), (492390, '''Milk and Honey'' was written with me being honest to myself, kind of pulling at the things that I hear the most and saying that out loud, and you know, that thing that we hear the most is most universal, and so that rings true with all folks. The language used in the poetry is extremely, extremely accessible.', 694, 0), (492391, 'For me, the power of the poetry in ''Milk and Honey'' is the feeling you get after finished reading the poem. It''s the emotion you feel once you''ve read the last word, and that is only possible when the diction is easy, and you don''t get stuck on every other word, you don''t know what the word means.', 694, 0), (492392, '''Hamilton'' is, of course, closely tied to the Obamas because Lin first performed the opening number at a White House poetry jam.', 69927, 0), (492393, 'I was one of those dark, quiet kids that wrote poetry.', 69514, 0), (492394, 'When superstition is allowed to perform the task of old age in dulling the human temperament, we can say goodbye to all excellence in poetry, in painting, and in music.', 2879, 0), (492395, 'When I arrived at Columbia, I gave up acting and became interested in all things French. French poetry, French history, French literature.', 12986, 0), (492396, 'Deals are my art form. Other people paint beautifully on canvas or write wonderful poetry. I like making deals, preferably big deals. That''s how I get my kicks.', 67486, 0), (492397, 'You can be intuitive when you''ve got a more expansive role. You can get into the poetry of telling the story rather than just pushing buttons.', 67567, 0), (492398, 'As I grew older - collapsing into my seventies, glimpsing ahead the cliffs of the eighties, colliding into eighty-five - poetry abandoned me.', 9086, 0), (492399, 'Prose is not so dependent on sound. The line of poetry, with the breaking of the line - to me, sound is the kind of doorway into poetry. And my sense of sound, or my ability to control it, lapsed or grew less.', 9086, 0), (492400, 'After a couple of years of public high school, I went to Exeter - an insane conglomeration of adolescent males in the wilderness, all of whom claimed to hate poetry.', 9086, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492401, 'I loathe the trivialization of poetry that happens in creative writing classes. Teachers set exercises to stimulate subject matter: Write a poem about an imaginary landscape with real people in it. Write about a place your parents lived in before you were born. We have enough terrible poetry around without encouraging more of it.', 9086, 0), (492402, 'I''ve always felt that poetry was particularly erotic, more than prose was... I say that you read poems not with your eyes and not with your ears, but with your mouth. You taste it.', 9086, 0), (492403, 'For better or worse, poetry is my life.', 9086, 0), (492404, 'Sound had always been my portal to poetry, but in the beginning, sound was imagined through the eye.', 9086, 0), (492405, 'Poetry is what I''ve done my whole life. And every important thing in my life had found itself into poems.', 9086, 0), (492406, 'In my life, I''ve seen enormous increase in the consumption of poetry. When I was young, there were virtually no poetry readings.', 9086, 0), (492407, 'Poetry offers works of art that are beautiful, like paintings, which are my second favorite work of the art, but there are also works of art that embody emotion and that are kind of school for feeling. They teach how to feel, and they do this by the means of their beauty of language.', 9086, 0), (492408, 'I was at Harvard with a whole bunch of poets, and that was very rare. They published a lot of books because there was an excitement after the war that translated into poetry.', 9086, 0), (492409, 'When it comes to poetry, I think partly the numbers of people attempting to write poems is probably a result or the reaction to technology.', 9086, 0), (492410, 'Every afternoon, I shut the door of my bedroom to write: Poetry was secret, dangerous, wicked and delicious.', 9086, 0), (492411, 'A song is a short composition for voice and instruments. It is a piece of sung poetry set to music. It is usually only a few minutes long.', 74863, 0), (492412, 'Poetry has been to me its own exceeding great reward it has given me the habit of wishing to discover the good and beautiful in all that meets and surrounds me. ', 1910, 0), (492413, 'I always loved singing and writing poetry. I always loved music, and I''ve loved writing my whole life. When I put them together, it was probably in my early 20s where I put words to music for the first time.', 68955, 0), (492414, 'When poetry is on the money, 12 words can slay you. I admire that greatly.', 24382, 0), (492415, 'I''m very attracted to poetry for all the reasons someone likes poetry. The notion of compression seems to fit my personality.', 24382, 0), (492416, 'I read a little bit of nonfiction and a lot of poetry. I think of poetry as my shot of whiskey when I don''t have time to savor a whole bottle of wine.', 14539, 0), (492417, 'The language of the Catholic Church - the liturgy, the prayer, the gospels - was in many ways my first poetry.', 14539, 0), (492418, 'I believed in fictional characters as if they were a part of real life. Poetry was important, too. My parents had memorized poems from their days attending school in New York City and loved reciting them. We all enjoyed listening to these poems and to music as well.', 14539, 0), (492419, 'Making love is, simply put, poetry in motion.', 69358, 0), (492420, 'I always read poetry before I write, to sensitize me to the rhythms and music of language.', 524, 0), (492421, 'History gives you insight of the same quality of truth as poetry or philosophy or a novel.', 20711, 0), (492422, 'Somehow, the words don''t have any vitality, any life to them, unless I can feel it marking on a paper. That''s how I start. Once I''m off, then I switch to the laptop. I think it would all just be prose if it started on a laptop - not that what I do is poetry.', 20711, 0), (492423, 'As a schoolboy, poetry seemed defined by preciousness. It was all very rarefied.', 20711, 0), (492424, 'The difficulty with poetry is that it doesn''t have the life that Shakespeare or Jane Austen have beyond the page. You can''t make a costume drama out of it. There''s no place for it to go except trapped inside its little book.', 20711, 0), (492425, 'The library was open for one hour after school let out. I hid there, looking at art books and reading poetry.', 9768, 0), (492426, 'Dancing is the poetry of the foot.', 8695, 0), (492427, 'Poetry is so vital to us until school spoils it.', 9597, 0), (492428, 'Anticipating that most poetry will be worse than carrying heavy luggage through O''Hare Airport, the public, to its loss, reads very little of it.', 9597, 0), (492429, 'I think the novel is not so much a literary genre, but a literary space, like a sea that is filled by many rivers. The novel receives streams of science, philosophy, poetry and contains all of these; it''s not simply telling a story.', 1357, 0), (492430, 'Nothing is too small. Nothing is too, quote-unquote, ordinary or insignificant. Those are the things that make up the measure of our days, and they''re the things that sustain us. And they''re the things that certainly can become worthy of poetry.', 9002, 0), (492431, 'I try to show what it is about language and music that enthralls, because I think those are the two elements of poetry.', 9002, 0), (492432, 'There are distinct duties of a poet laureate. I plan a reading series at the Library of Congress and advise the librarian. The rest is how I want to promote poetry.', 9002, 0), (492433, 'I was apprehensive. I feared every time I talked about poetry, it would be filtered through the lens of race, sex, and age.', 9002, 0), (492434, 'I see a resurgence of interest in poetry. I am less optimistic about the prospects for the arts when it comes to federal funding.', 9002, 0), (492435, 'The poetry that sustains me is when I feel that, for a minute, the clouds have parted and I''ve seen ecstasy or something.', 9002, 0), (492436, 'I think one of the things that people tend to forget is that poets do write out of life. It isn''t some set piece that then gets put up on the shelf, but that the impetus, the real instigation for poetry is everything that''s happening around us.', 9002, 0), (492437, 'Not too many people know it, but when I was in junior high, I was a pretty tough kid and was the leader of a street gang. Well, OK, it was less a street gang than an Ecology Club. We were pretty intimidating, though, and had our own meeting room until we got run out of there by a bunch of thugs from the Poetry Society.', 33965, 0), (492438, 'I want to be the best advocate and promoter for poetry that I can be.', 8857, 0), (492439, 'From the catbird seat, I''ve found poetry to be the necessary utterance it has always been in America.', 8857, 0), (492440, 'Dismissals of poetry are nothing new. It''s easy to dismiss poetry if one has not read much of it.', 8857, 0), (492441, 'The first thing I tried to do in the months after losing my mother was to write a poem. I found myself turning to poetry in the way so many people do - to make sense of losses. And I wrote pretty bad poems about it. But it did feel that the poem was the only place that could hold this grief.', 8857, 0), (492442, 'I think I felt at some point that I couldn''t understand poetry or that it was beyond me or it didn''t speak to my experience. I think that was because I hadn''t yet found the right poems to invite me in.', 8857, 0), (492443, 'My father, Eric Trethewey, is a poet, so I had one right inside the house. And on long trips, he''d tell me, if I got bored in the car, to write a poem about it. And I did find that poetry was a way for me, I think as it for a lot of people, to articulate those things that seem hardest to say.', 8857, 0), (492444, 'I think poetry''s always a kind of faith. It is the kind that I have.', 8857, 0), (492445, 'Even though I am the daughter of a poet, and my stepmother is also a poet, growing up, I didn''t think I could understand poetry; I didn''t think that it had any relevance to my life, the feelings that I endured on a day-to-day basis, until I was introduced to the right poem.', 8857, 0), (492446, 'I think people turn to poetry more often than they think they do, or encounter it in more ways than they think that they do. I think we forget the places that we encounter it, say, in songs or in other little bits and pieces of things that we may have remembered from childhood.', 8857, 0), (492447, 'I think the biggest thing that I have to do is to remind people that poetry is there for us to turn to not only to remind us that we''re not alone - for example, if we are grieving the loss of someone - but also to help us celebrate our joys. That''s why so many people I know who''ve gotten married will have a poem read at the wedding.', 8857, 0), (492448, 'Poetry''s a thing that belongs to everyone.', 8857, 0), (492449, '''NewsHour'' is very interested in poetry, but they''re also interested in not just that something''s cute to add on at the end of their programming, but something that actually is integrated into the news.', 8857, 0), (492450, 'I''ve been most happy to be an advocate for the kinds of grassroots things that people are doing who care about poetry.', 8857, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492451, 'I like the beauty of Faulkner''s poetry. But I don''t like his themes, not at all.', 9731, 0), (492452, 'I spent many years of my life as an economist and demographer. I was finally distracted by writing my novels and poetry. I''m enormously happy that was the case. I feel that with writing I have found my metier.', 3948, 0), (492453, 'You have to learn a few things, which you do along the way, but basically, poetry is a matter of the ear. Iambic pentameters or what constitutes a stanza comes naturally - your ears will know.', 3948, 0), (492454, 'Why do writers, say, give up a job in economics and decide to write poetry? Or, why do they give up a job in a bank and decide to paint, like Krishan Khanna? They want to convey something.', 3948, 0), (492455, 'Everyone sort of sees his own life and times as being ephemeral. One thinks that everything good or important that happened, happened in the past. But I think that seeing scenes that you are used to, but with the heightening effects of poetry, perhaps makes you value your life and times more than you might otherwise do.', 3948, 0), (492456, 'Those books of mine that are remunerative - I''m not talking about poetry here - take years to write, and I am never sure they''ll be successful. So writing is a risk in more senses than one.', 3948, 0), (492457, 'You know, I can imagine not writing a novel and writing poetry only.', 3948, 0), (492458, 'The Lord''s Prayer is the most perfect piece of poetry. I always feel at peace and moved when I recite it.', 57412, 0), (492459, 'The poet doesn''t invent. He listens.', 2343, 0), (492460, 'A true poet does not bother to be poetical. Nor does a nursery gardener scent his roses.', 2343, 0), (492461, 'Poetry is indispensable - if I only knew what for.', 2343, 0), (492462, 'The sentences I write have their roots in song and poetry, and take their bearings from music and painting, as much as from the need to impart mere information, or mirror anything. I am not a realist writer, even if I seem like one.', 27793, 0), (492463, 'Thinking in its lower grades, is comparable to paper money, and in its higher forms it is a kind of poetry.', 62533, 0), (492464, 'When I was in college, I used to write little ditties and short stories and poetry for my friends. Writing a book is another thing. It is so much different from my traditional day of dirty fingernails and greasy hair and hot pans.', 70268, 0), (492465, 'I actually remember celebrating National Poetry Day at school I remember having to write and read a load. ', 72755, 0), (492466, 'Most poetry in the modern age has retreated to the private sphere, turning its back on the political realm.', 1914, 0), (492467, 'Poetry is the most subtle of the literary arts, and students grow more ingenious by the year at avoiding it. If they can nip around Milton, duck under Blake and collapse gratefully into the arms of Jane Austen, a lot of them will.', 1914, 0), (492468, 'When I started writing poetry, it was always in very hip-hop influenced spaces: Someone would teach a Nas song side-by-side with a Gwendolyn Brooks poem, and we''d talk about the connections between those things.', 73214, 0), (492469, 'I have a band called M&O. We were working on our first album in 2011 or 2012. We were looking for people to collaborate with, and I met Chance through a Young Chicago Authors poetry slam.', 73214, 0), (492470, 'It was through poetry I learned just to appreciate my own voice and to not think of my voice in terms of what it needs to be able to do, but what it can do.', 73214, 0), (492471, 'My artistic manifesto exists in the world as poetry. So even though most of the things that I''ve done have been on other people''s projects or could be pigeonholed in certain ways, that''s not how I perceive myself.', 73214, 0), (492472, 'I really liked ''Blk Girl Art.'' It''s like a manifesto saying why I create, whether it''s poetry or music.', 73214, 0), (492473, 'If a poem is not memorable, there''s probably something wrong. One of the problems of free verse is that much of the free verse poetry is not memorable.', 68479, 0), (492474, 'I think that it''s more likely that in my 60s and 70s I will be writing poetry rather than fiction.', 68479, 0), (492475, 'I did not have a very literary background. I came to poetry from the sciences and mathematics, and also through an interest in Japanese and Chinese poetry in translation.', 68479, 0), (492476, 'You have to really dive deep back into yourself and get rid of so much modern analytical categorization. It''s one of the great things poetry does.', 68479, 0), (492477, 'The great watershed of modern poetry is French, more than English.', 68479, 0), (492478, 'Among the American contemporaries I read with most enjoyment are several North Carolinians. I think the best poetry being written these days is being written by Southerners.', 68479, 0), (492479, 'The Language Poets are writing only about language itself. The Ashbery poets are writing only about poetry itself. That seems to me a kind of dead end.', 68479, 0), (492480, 'Poetry, almost by definition, calls attention to its language and form.', 68479, 0), (492481, 'The decision to write in prose instead of poetry is made more by the readers than by writers. Almost no one is interested in reading narrative in verse.', 68479, 0), (492482, 'Teaching writing over the years intrudes on your own writing in important ways, taking away some of the excitement of poetry.', 68479, 0), (492483, 'I don''t think poetry is something that can be taught. We can encourage young writers, but what you can''t teach them is the very essence of poetry.', 68479, 0), (492484, 'I don''t think the creative writing industry has helped American poetry.', 68479, 0), (492485, 'Some people swear by writing courses, but whether it really helps American poetry, I have doubts.', 68479, 0), (492486, 'I don''t think American poetry has gotten any better in the past 35 years. Oddly enough, creative writing programs seem to have been good for fiction, and I would not have predicted that.', 68479, 0), (492487, 'I love to compare different time frames. Poetry can evoke the time of the subject. By a very careful choice of words you can evoke an era, completely throw the poem into a different time scale.', 68479, 0), (492488, 'One of the most powerful devices of poetry is the use of distortions. You can go from talking about the way a minute passes to the way a century passes, or a lifetime.', 68479, 0), (492489, 'A poem in form still has to have voice, gesture, a sense of discovery, a metaphoric connection, as any poetry does.', 68479, 0), (492490, 'The fact that something is in a rhymed form or in blank verse will not make it good poetry.', 68479, 0), (492491, 'What actually makes poetry poetry is of course impossible to define. We recognize it when we hear it, when we see it, but we can''t define it.', 68479, 0), (492492, 'The idea of avant-garde art is a very suspicious thing to me, the idea that poetry is new and it keeps being new the way Chevrolets every year are new.', 68479, 0), (492493, 'Part of what we love about poetry is the fact that it seems ancient, that it has an authority of ancient language and ancient form, and that it''s timeless, that it reaches back.', 68479, 0), (492494, 'I learned to impersonate the kind of person that talks about poetry. It comes from teaching, I think.', 68479, 0), (492495, 'And, I mean, I think poetry does need to be met to some extent, especially, I guess, 19th century poetry, and for me, it''s just been so worth the effort. It''s like I''m planting a garden in my head.', 72476, 0), (492496, 'As for how criticism of Keats'' poetry relates to criticism of my own work, I''ll leave that for others to decide.', 72476, 0), (492497, 'I have to admit that I had a lot of problems with poetry.', 72476, 0), (492498, 'Poetry, especially traditional Iranian poetry, is very good at looking at things from a number of different angles simultaneously.', 67520, 0), (492499, 'My feeling is that poetry will wither on the vine if you don''t regularly come back to the simplest fundamentals of the poem: rhythm, rhyme, simple subjects - love, death, war.', 4219, 0), (492500, 'Lyric poetry is, of course, musical in origin. I do know that what happened to poetry in the twentieth century was that it began to be written for the page. When it''s a question of typography, why not? Poets have done beautiful things with typography - Apollinaire''s ''Calligrammes,'' that sort of thing.', 4219, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492501, 'English poetry begins whenever we decide to say the modern English language begins, and it extends as far as we decide to say that the English language extends.', 4219, 0), (492502, 'Some people think that English poetry begins with the Anglo-Saxons. I don''t, because I can''t accept that there is any continuity between the traditions of Anglo-Saxon poetry and those established in English poetry by the time of, say, Shakespeare. And anyway, Anglo-Saxon is a different language, which has to be learned.', 4219, 0), (492503, 'When we study Shakespeare on the page, for academic purposes, we may require all kinds of help. Generally, we read him in modern spelling and with modern punctuation, and with notes. But any poetry that is performed - from song lyric to tragic speech - must make its point, as it were, without reference back.', 4219, 0), (492504, 'Composers need words, but they do not necessarily need poetry. The Russian composer, Aleksandr Mossolov, who chose texts from newspaper small ads, had a good point to make. With revolutionary music, any text can be set to work.', 4219, 0), (492505, 'A glance at the history of European poetry is enough to inform us that rhyme itself is not indispensable. Latin poetry in the classical age had no use for it, and the kind of Latin poetry that does rhyme - as for instance the medieval ''Carmina Burana'' - tends to be somewhat crude stuff in comparison with the classical verse that doesn''t.', 4219, 0), (492506, 'Great poetry does not have to be technically intricate.', 4219, 0), (492507, 'The iambic pentameter owes its pre-eminence in English poetry to its genius for variation. Good blank verse does not sound like a series of identically measured lines. It sounds like a series of subtle variations on the same theme.', 4219, 0), (492508, 'The voice is raised, and that is where poetry begins. And even today, in the prolonged aftermath of modernism, in places where ''open form'' or free verse is the orthodoxy, you will find a memory of that raising of the voice in the term ''heightened speech.''', 4219, 0), (492509, 'One problem we face comes from the lack of any agreed sense of how we should be working to train ourselves to write poetry.', 4219, 0), (492510, 'In the writing of poetry we never know anything for sure. We will never know if we have ''trained'' or ''practised'' enough. We will never be able to say that we have reached grade eight, or that we have left the grades behind and are now embarked on an advanced training.', 4219, 0), (492511, 'In the winter of 1940, ''The Atlantic Monthly'' invited Peter Viereck, a twenty-three-year-old Harvard graduate who had won the college''s top essay and poetry prizes, to write about ''the meaning of young liberalism for the present age.''', 40818, 0), (492512, 'Poetry always, always, always is a key piece of democracy.', 30989, 0), (492513, 'As things get worse, poetry gets better because it becomes more necessary.', 30989, 0), (492514, 'I wasn''t afraid of being poor. I didn''t want to live in a big house. I''m the perfect size for poetry. I can move around.', 30989, 0), (492515, 'In Arlington, people would laugh at you if you tried to get people to look at your drawings or listen to your poetry. It was like you thought you were special.', 30989, 0), (492516, 'Poetry from the bottom up is an act of selection: you kind of feel your way through the crowds of poems. The good ones came forward a long time ago, and the bad ones fell away.', 30989, 0), (492517, 'Poetry and novels are lists of our devotions. We love the feel of making the marks as the feelings are rising and falling.', 30989, 0), (492518, 'Prose, poetry, and drawings stand side by side in a very democratic way in my work.', 5995, 0), (492519, 'I''d park myself in the bookstore and read with one eye on everyone coming in. I remember reading a Robert Bly book of poetry.', 19941, 0), (492520, 'I lived a pretty chaotic life. I went to England, and I moved around, and there were a lot of things that I was interested in. I wrote poetry. I took photographs. I was a musician and all sorts of things. Nothing brilliant, but I did all these different things.', 67094, 0), (492521, 'Watching and learning from the great Josette Bushell-Mingo, who was playing Cleopatra in Antony and Cleopatra at the time, and then to return to the same stage six months later playing a lead role, was incredible - I fell in love with the poetry and the breadth of the language so much that I didn''t want it to end.', 69940, 0), (492522, 'I never thought I''d be doing poetry books. I never really studied poetry. But the first one I did was after my mother died, and I realized that people sort of think and talk about her style and fashion, but in fact, what made her the person she was was really her love of reading and ideas.', 10105, 0), (492523, 'Poetry is really a way of sharing feelings and ideas.', 10105, 0), (492524, 'The biggest problem is people are afraid of poetry, think they can''t understand it or that it will be boring.', 10105, 0), (492525, 'The mystical poetry of William Blake''s artwork also forms the basis for the album cover.', 68023, 0), (492526, 'Perhaps no person can be a poet, or even enjoy poetry, without a certain unsoundness of mind.', 13860, 0), (492527, 'As civilization advances, poetry almost necessarily declines.', 13860, 0), (492528, 'I liked Yeats! That wild Irishman. I really loved his love of language, his flow. His chaotic ideas seemed to me just the right thing for a poet. Passion! He was always on the right side. He may be wrongheaded, but his heart was always on the right side. He wrote beautiful poetry.', 9773, 0), (492529, 'I was trained as an actress. But I wasn''t a very convincing actress, so I started doing punk poetry and then fell into doing stand-up.', 71840, 0), (492530, 'When I was in college, I wrote poetry very seriously, and then once I had started writing short stories, I didn''t go back to poetry, partially because I felt like I understood how incredibly difficult it was.', 8274, 0), (492531, 'Poetry is often the art of overhearing yourself say things you didn''t know you knew. It is a learned skill to force yourself to articulate your life, your present world or your possibilities for the future.', 19315, 0), (492532, 'There''s a fierce practicality and empiricism which the whole imaginative, lyrical aspect of poetry comes from.', 19315, 0), (492533, 'Poetry is a street fighter. It has sharp elbows. It can look after itself. Poetry can''t be used for manipulation it''s why you never see good poetry in advertising. ', 19315, 0), (492534, 'By definition, poetry works with qualities and dynamics that mainstream society is reluctant to face head-on. It''s an interesting phenomenon that by necessity, poetry is just below the radar.', 19315, 0), (492535, 'It is the province of poetry to be more realistic and present than the artificial narratives of an outer discourse, and not afraid of the truthful difficulty of the average human life.', 19315, 0), (492536, 'Poetry carries the imagery which is large enough for the kind of life we want for ourselves.', 19315, 0), (492537, 'Unfortunately, poetry is not born in noise, in crowds, or on a bus. There have to be four walls and the certainty that the telephone will not ring. That''s what writing is all about.', 23289, 0), (492538, 'Poetic talent doesn''t operate in a vacuum. There is a spirit of Polish poetry.', 23289, 0), (492539, 'Everyone needs solitude, especially a person who is used to thinking about what she experiences. Solitude is very important in my work as a mode of inspiration, but isolation is not good in this respect. I am not writing poetry about isolation.', 23289, 0), (492540, 'Solitude is very important in my work as a mode of inspiration, but isolation is not good in this respect. I am not writing poetry about isolation.', 23289, 0), (492541, 'Thomas Davis was a great man where poetry is concerned, and a better than Thomas Moore. All over Ireland his poetry is, and he would have done other things but that he died young.', 21592, 0), (492542, 'I''m not a great poetry fan.', 68969, 0), (492543, 'Colloquial poetry is to the real art as the barber''s wax dummy is to sculpture.', 8630, 0), (492544, 'And New York is the most beautiful city in the world? It is not far from it. No urban night is like the night there... Squares after squares of flame, set up and cut into the aether. Here is our poetry, for we have pulled down the stars to our will.', 8630, 0), (492545, 'In my late teenage years, I developed a real passion for it, and wrote a lot of poetry.', 5214, 0), (492546, 'Reading a piece of poetry with no beat in front of 20 people is way more challenging than rocking for 10,000 people.', 16895, 0), (492547, 'I read, read enormously on all different fields of Islamic thought, from philosophy to Islamic literature, poetry, exegeses, knowledge of the Hadith, the teachings of the prophet. That''s how I trained myself. And then I was appointed imam by a Sufi master from Istanbul, Turkey.', 68724, 0), (492548, 'I think going from doing TV and straight plays to Shakespeare is weird enough because you have this heightened language, and you are telling a story through metric poetry. But I think music is that place beyond poetry.', 69145, 0), (492549, 'Poetry always runs away from you - it''s very difficult to grasp it, and every time you read it, depending on your conditions, you will have a different grasp of it. Whereas with a novel, once you have read it, you have grasped it.', 21523, 0), (492550, 'My favourite room in my house is easily the top room, which is a bedroom but also a bathroom, with a big, wooden carved bath, two huge fireplaces and a raised bit in the corner for performances. I''ve had some really lovely parties and poetry readings up there.', 1428, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492551, 'I know I''m not a wordsmith. And I don''t write poetry. Sometimes I think I should, because it''s really helpful. But I always wanted to write novels.', 66, 0), (492552, 'I definitely used to write a lot at school. Comic poetry and drawings about people.', 74135, 0), (492553, 'Poetry is for me Eucharistic. You take someone else''s suffering into your body, their passion comes into your body, and in doing that you commune, you take communion, you make a community with others.', 2326, 0), (492554, 'Poetry privileges music and is aesthetically more challenging. Prose privileges information and is emotionally more challenging.', 2326, 0), (492555, 'Prose cannot compete with the economy of poetry, the ability to have a full artistic experience in a short period of time.', 2326, 0), (492556, 'Hebrew as a contemporary language, especially for poetry, is no longer the language of the Bible; but neither is it not the language of the Bible.', 30964, 0), (492557, 'I''m conscious of a series of circles working its way through my life. And at this particular moment I have come round to the beginning of my writing cycle. It begins with poetry. There''s hardly a day that goes past on which I don''t write poetry.', 1028, 0), (492558, 'I began my writing life as a poet, so poetry has always been fundamental. I evolved from poetry to journalism to stories to novels. But poetry was always there.', 1028, 0), (492559, 'I''ve been writing since I was 10 or 11. I started with poetry because that was the easiest thing. It just kind of came naturally. I think at that time West Coast hip hop was huge; all these kids around me were like, ''I want to be a rapper.'' But I''m a white girl, not going to be a rapper.', 26862, 0), (492560, 'I''ve always loved the poetry in ''Pale Fire.'' I think it''s wonderful.', 24272, 0), (492561, 'Poetry is really about your mental state or intellectual, and where you are, and you''re trying to evoke that, explain it to yourself, whatever, you''re trying to dig into it, analyse yourself.', 24272, 0), (492562, 'I think poetry was always where I went to deal with my deepest feelings.', 24272, 0), (492563, 'I''ve always used poetry to explain myself to myself. These things just sat in my psyche and then came out.', 24272, 0), (492564, 'I love poetry; it''s my primary literary interest, and I suppose the kind of reading you do when you are reading poems - close reading - can carry over into how you read other things.', 24272, 0), (492565, 'Poetry is not mainstream, but then neither is serious fiction, really. But I don''t think there''s a lot to worry about in this particular ''problem''. Why does art have to be mainstream to be significant?', 24272, 0), (492566, 'I think poetry should be read very much like prose, except that the line breaks should be acknowledged somehow.', 24272, 0), (492567, 'For me, poetry is a situation - a state of being, a way of facing life and facing history.', 31617, 0), (492568, 'I came to poetry through the urgent need to denounce injustice, exploitation, humiliation. I know that''s not enough to change the world. But to remain silent would have been a kind of intolerable complicity.', 31617, 0), (492569, 'I love to read poetry but I haven''t written anything that I''m willing to show anybody.', 1458, 0), (492570, 'You will not find poetry anywhere unless you bring some of it with you.', 8895, 0), (492571, 'Publishing a volume of verse is like dropping a rose petal down the Grand Canyon and waiting for the echo.', 2692, 0), (492572, 'Poetry is what Milton saw when he went blind.', 2692, 0), (492573, 'All voices are important, and yet it seems that people of color have a lot to say, particularly if you look through the poetry of young people - a lot of questions and a lot of concerns about immigration and security issues, you name it - big questions.', 8822, 0), (492574, 'I gave my voice to poetry.', 8822, 0), (492575, 'Poetry, as odd as it is, and as hard to figure out as it is, many times, it''s almost something that we''re used to. It''s kind of like a dream language that we had centuries ago, so that when we speak poetically or write a poem about what''s going on, a real difficult issue that''s facing our communities, people listen.', 8822, 0), (492576, 'San Diego shaped me a lot. The visual landscapes, the emotional panoramas, the teachers and mentors I had from the third grade through San Diego High - it''s all a big part of the poetry fountain that I continue to drink from.', 8822, 0), (492577, 'The banner of the project is ''Casa de Colores.'' Under that banner, I''m going to invite people to do a lot of good things. Perhaps working in groups, working on poetry.', 8822, 0), (492578, 'My mother was a washerwoman - or a woman that cleaned houses in Texas... in Plano, Texas - who always loved poetry and always loved stories.', 8822, 0), (492579, 'I write all the time - I write poetry, I love to write.', 36389, 0), (492580, 'I''m not a writer. I think I can write short stories and poetry, but film writing, brilliant film writing, is a talent - you can''t just do it like that.', 70721, 0), (492581, 'It''s like I understand images and some people understand poetry.', 70721, 0), (492582, 'It''s bad poetry executed by people that can''t sing. That''s my definition of Rap.', 68500, 0), (492583, 'My favorite subject probably was math. I love math. Figures just intrigue me. I was really good at math. English probably was my worst subject. But I used to write a lot of poetry. I used to write poetry all the time.', 70723, 0), (492584, 'Poetry is at the centre of my life, too, emotionally speaking, and intellectually speaking - it''s just that I''m one of those people who enjoy doing other stuff as well.', 8625, 0), (492585, 'I''m not precisely saying that a really good board meeting at the MLA (Museums, Libraries and Archives Coucil) makes me want to go and write poetry, but there is a pleasure in doing that sort of thing well.', 8625, 0), (492586, 'I wish I''d been better able to resist the sense of obligation to write some of the poems I did. It''s in the nature of commissioned work to be written too much from the side of your mind that knows what it''s doing, which dries up the poetry.', 8625, 0), (492587, 'In a general way, I want to be a kind of flag-waver, bunting hanger-up, drum-beater, you name it, for poetry.', 8625, 0), (492588, 'Thanks partly to the kind of poets that we now have and partly to funding, there''s been a gigantic shift in the way poetry is perceived... Poems on the Underground, poets in schools, football clubs, zoos.', 8625, 0), (492589, 'I wanted to reimagine the role, in a way that was respectful of its traditional responsibilities but made them part of a wider pattern of poetry about national incidents, events, preoccupations; and to spend a great deal of time going to schools trying to demystify poetry.', 8625, 0), (492590, 'More people are reading poetry now than at any time in the history of the human race.', 8625, 0), (492591, 'There is something about poetry beyond prose logic, there is mystery in it, not to be explained but admired.', 4028, 0), (492592, 'I got scouted for modeling on the street. I''m such a tomboy - still am. I just never thought about modeling before, but I thought, ''Ooh, interesting, similar world, perhaps it''s a way into something.'' Then, I was on my third photo shoot ever, and Adam Leech from ''Downtown Abbey'' saw me reading poetry and asked me to recite some.', 75008, 0), (492593, 'All through childhood, I wrote verses and mysteries. There is, for me, one connection: structure. My poetry is metrical, rhyming.', 16726, 0), (492594, 'Those who have never entered upon scientific pursuits know not a tithe of the poetry by which they are surrounded.', 3690, 0), (492595, 'I always credited my mother with inspiring me to be a writer because she was such a passionate reader. She read poetry to me as a child. But rather late in life, I''ve come to appreciate my father, the accountant. He was a solid, organized, get-the-job-done kind of person-and you need that piece of it to be a writer, too.', 29209, 0), (492596, 'I thought it would be a funny concept to publish a book about stand-up comedy with Faber, the poetry publisher, and to apply to stand-up the same sort of weight of annotation that you would to a classic work of literature, an epic poem. I thought that would be funny.', 17109, 0), (492597, 'I accept all interpretations of my films. The only reality is before the camera. Each film I make is kind of a return to poetry for me, or at least an attempt to create a poem.', 74509, 0), (492598, 'The poet is a specialist in something which everyone practises. Herein, poetry differs from the other arts. Everyone does not practise music or painting or even dancing, but everyone without exception puts together words poetically every day of his life.', 8656, 0), (492599, 'Everyone is not able, or inclined, to write poetry in the narrower sense any more than everyone is qualified to take part in a walking race. But just as all of us can and do walk, so all of us can and do use language poetically.', 8656, 0), (492600, 'The rules or ''laws'' of poetry are only tentative devices, an approximate scheme. There is no Sinaitic recipe for poetry, for the individual poem is the norm.', 8656, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492601, 'The novel is born of disillusionment; the poem, of despair.', 9298, 0), (492602, 'Poetry is adolescence fermented, and thus preserved.', 2800, 0), (492603, 'Everything is complicated; if that were not so, life and poetry and everything else would be a bore.', 2547, 0), (492604, 'To me, art begets art. Painting feeds the eye just as poetry feeds the ear, which is to say that both feed the soul.', 2779, 0), (492605, 'If you put a real leaf and a silk leaf side by side, you''ll see something of the difference between Homer''s poetry and anyone else''s. There seem to be real leaves still alive in the ''Iliad,'' real animals, real people, real light attending everything.', 71066, 0), (492606, 'Poetry for me is as much a spiritual practice as sexual ecstasy is.', 8885, 0), (492607, 'I sometimes talk about the making of a poem within the poem.', 2187, 0), (492608, 'Everyone thinks they''re going to write one book of poems or one novel.', 29223, 0), (492609, 'Poetry remembers that it was an oral art before it was a written art.', 284, 0), (492610, 'I know nothing new except that Herr Gellert, the Leipzig poet, is dead, and has written no more poetry since his death.', 611, 0), (492611, 'There is one type of ideal woman very seldom described in poetry - the old maid, the woman whom sorrow or misfortune prevents from fulfilling her natural destiny.', 2909, 0), (492612, 'No poem is easily grasped so why should any reader expect fast results? ', 75880, 0), (492613, 'Sometimes poetry is inspired by the conversation entered into by reading other poems.', 75880, 0), (492614, 'An experienced reader uses the poem as an agent of inquiry. This makes poetry very exciting, unstable, and interactive.', 75880, 0), (492615, 'I studied poetry in college and for a year in an MFA program. As time went on, my poems got more and more complicated. What I was really trying to do was tell stories.', 11939, 0), (492616, 'I like poems that are little games.', 75881, 0), (492617, 'I''m quite sure that most writers would sustain real poetry if they could, but it takes devotion and talent.', 42780, 0), (492618, 'I was always making up rhymes. But I never thought that poetry would become my life.', 259, 0), (492619, 'Science and art, or by the same token, poetry and prose differ from one another like a journey and an excursion. The purpose of the journey is its goal, the purpose of an excursion is the process.', 59853, 0), (492620, 'I''ll try anything, but the pig testicles in Taiwan were a little much. Eh, it wasn''t half bad. There was this one dish I had there, the translation is, ''The Monk Jumps over the Fence.'' It''s a fish dish with all these spices. It was beautiful, man - it was poetry. It had a whole story.', 73206, 0), (492621, 'Poetry is a beautiful way of spoiling prose, and the laborious art of exchanging plain sense for harmony.', 1081, 0), (492622, 'I believe in the power of poetry, which gives me reasons to look ahead and identify a glint of light.', 8723, 0), (492623, 'I see poetry as spiritual medicine.', 8723, 0), (492624, 'Against barbarity, poetry can resist only by confirming its attachment to human fragility like a blade of grass growing on a wall while armies march by.', 8723, 0), (492625, 'That sense of a life in natural objects, which in most poetry is but a rhetorical artifice, was, then, in Wordsworth the assertion of what was for him almost literal fact.', 11179, 0), (492626, 'Still, language is resilient, and poetry when it is pressured simply goes underground.', 41724, 0), (492627, 'I really love poetry. I''m a big E.E. Cummings fan and a big Walt Whitman fan, and I have a big book of poetry.', 75145, 0), (492628, 'I didn''t know how to weigh ideas about poetry. Nothing in the life I lived as a student - and later as wife and mother at the suburban edge of Dublin - suggested I had the wherewithal to do so. But I did have a unit of measurement. It was the measure of my own life.', 8802, 0), (492629, 'Usually a life turned into a poem is misrepresented.', 5859, 0), (492630, 'Pain is filtered in a poem so that it becomes finally, in the end, pleasure.', 5859, 0), (492631, 'You don''t help people in your poems. I''ve been trying to help people all my life - that''s my trouble.', 21611, 0), (492632, 'There''ll always be working people in my poems because I grew up with them, and I am a poet of memory.', 8739, 0), (492633, 'I wonder if I ever thought of an ideal reader... I guess when I was in my 20s and in New York and maybe even in my early 30s, I would write for my wife Janice... mainly for my poet friends and my wife, who was very smart about poetry.', 49609, 0), (492634, 'We all need ways to express ourselves, and poetry is one of mine.', 8654, 0), (492635, 'Poetry seems to sink into us the way prose doesn''t. I can still quote verses I learned when I was very young, but I have trouble remembering one line of a novel I just finished reading.', 8654, 0), (492636, 'Children seem naturally drawn to poetry - it''s some combination of the rhyme, rhythm, and the words themselves.', 8654, 0), (492637, 'I started out as a writer. Poetry and prose and also kind of satirical David Sedaris-esque stuff.', 75882, 0), (492638, 'Eloquence is the poetry of prose.', 70801, 0), (492639, 'The first function of poetry is to tell the truth, to learn how to do that, to find out what you really feel and what you really think.', 8754, 0), (492640, 'I wanted to write the kind of poetry that people read and remembered, that they lived by - the kinds of lines that I carried with me from moment to moment on a given day without even having chosen to.', 41866, 0), (492641, 'I come here to speak poetry. It will always be in the grass. It will also be necessary to bend down to hear it. It will always be too simple to be discussed in assemblies.', 925, 0), (492642, 'That is to say, epic poetry has been invented many times and independently; but, as the needs which prompted the invention have been broadly similar, so the invention itself has been.', 66957, 0), (492643, 'Do-gooders are easily overlooked. We''re supposed to be soft, touchy-feely types, who wear Birkenstocks, compost everything, and write poetry by candlelight.', 69966, 0), (492644, 'The same people who are murdered slowly in the mechanized slaughterhouses of work are also arguing, singing, drinking, dancing, making love, holding the streets, picking up weapons and inventing a new poetry.', 17528, 0), (492645, 'You don''t have to suffer to be a poet adolescence is enough suffering for anyone. ', 12892, 0), (492646, 'Poetry lies its way to the truth.', 12892, 0), (492647, 'I used to write sonnets and various things, and moved from there into writing prose, which, incidentally, is a lot more interesting than poetry, including the rhythms of prose.', 32421, 0), (492648, 'Poetry is the mother-tongue of the human race.', 59770, 0), (492649, 'Even when poetry has a meaning, as it usually has, it may be inadvisable to draw it out... Perfect understanding will sometimes almost extinguish pleasure.', 7209, 0), (492650, 'If you read quickly to get through a poem to what it means, you have missed the body of the poem.', 20196, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492651, 'I think there are things in my story that have helped my creativity. Your father being killed, for instance, is one of the best things that could happen to a kid if he''s going to write poetry or songs.', 16030, 0), (492652, 'We all write poems it is simply that poets are the ones who write in words. ', 1452, 0), (492653, 'Poetry is the deification of reality.', 1102, 0), (492654, 'No, what I should really like to do right now, in the full blaze of lights, before this illustrious assembly, is to shower every one of you with gifts, with flowers, with offerings of poetry - to be young once more, to ride on the crest of the wave.', 7861, 0), (492655, 'Cut quarrels out of literature, and you will have very little history or drama or fiction or epic poetry left.', 70200, 0), (492656, 'I think that one possible definition of our modern culture is that it is one in which nine-tenths of our intellectuals can''t read any poetry.', 4896, 0), (492657, 'To a poet the mere making of a poem can seem to solve the problem of truth, but only a problem of art is solved in poetry.', 75160, 0), (492658, 'The end of poetry is not to create a physical condition which shall give pleasure to the mind... The end of poetry is not an after-effect, not a pleasurable memory of itself, but an immediate, constant and even unpleasant insistence upon itself.', 75160, 0), (492659, 'Well, I write a lot of poetry - that''s where it usually all starts. I definitely want to show you guys sides of me - love, loss, heartbreak - all of that good stuff!', 71671, 0), (492660, 'Each memorable verse of a true poet has two or three times the written content.', 4004, 0), (492661, 'However, if a poem can be reduced to a prose sentence, there can''t be much to it.', 75883, 0), (492662, 'I used to joke that if acting didn''t work out, poetry was my commonsense fallback.', 75884, 0), (492663, 'I wrote poetry, journals, and, especially, plays for the neighborhood kids to perform. I had an ordinary, happy childhood. Nothing much was going on, but I had fun.', 820, 0), (492664, 'Society''s dark hull drifts further and further away. It is this place - the place of our separation, our distinction - that much of his poetry occupies.', 7851, 0), (492665, 'I was kind of an outcast in school ''cause I always kept to myself and was writing poetry and then going on tour with my brother band all the time, so kids didn''t know what to make of me.', 22665, 0), (492666, 'And inasmuch as the bridge is a symbol of all such poetry as I am interested in writing it is my present fancy that a year from now I''ll be more contented working in an office than ever before.', 9079, 0), (492667, 'Painting (like poetry) chooses from universals what is most apposite. It brings together, in a single imaginary being, circumstances and characteristics which occur in nature in many different persons.', 75022, 0), (492668, 'The job of the poet is to render the world - to see it and report it without loss, without perversion. No poet ever talks about feelings. Only sentimental people do.', 11546, 0), (492669, 'Reality only reveals itself when it is illuminated by a ray of poetry.', 30266, 0), (492670, 'How do poems grow? They grow out of your life.', 2655, 0), (492671, 'The poem is a little myth of man''s capacity of making life meaningful. And in the end, the poem is not a thing we see-it is, rather, a light by which we may see-and what we see is life.', 2655, 0), (492672, 'You don''t make a poem with ideas, but with words.', 9057, 0), (492673, 'Freedom is poetry, taking liberties with words, breaking the rules of normal speech, violating common sense. Freedom is violence.', 43221, 0), (492674, 'I intended an Ode, And it turned to a Sonnet.', 12929, 0), (492675, 'A poem can have an impact, but you can''t expect an audience to understand all the nuances.', 75885, 0), (492676, 'I''ve always written poetry and lyrics. My first husband, who was a musician, we wrote a bunch of songs together.', 74495, 0), (492677, 'There is the view that poetry should improve your life. I think people confuse it with the Salvation Army.', 8842, 0), (492678, 'Don''t call my lyrics poetry. It''s an insult to real poets.', 75886, 0), (492679, 'I don''t look on poetry as closed works. I feel they''re going on all the time in my head and I occasionally snip off a length.', 8842, 0), (492680, 'The mystic purchases a moment of exhilaration with a lifetime of confusion; and the confusion is infectious and destructive. It is confusing and destructive to try and explain anything in terms of anything else, poetry in terms of psychology.', 39411, 0), (492681, 'I''ve been surprised to learn how many people love poetry. It''s beautiful to see that people want poetry in their lives.', 19906, 0), (492682, 'It''s always good to show that poetry isn''t the little depressed lyric people believe it to be, that it''s something bigger.', 75887, 0), (492683, 'In Bonn, where I studied for a year, I changed from classical to Romance philology, taught there by its great founder, F. Diez, and at the beginning of 1852, I received the doctorate for a dissertation on the refrain in Provencal poetry.', 75888, 0), (492684, 'Poetry is an orphan of silence. The words never quite equal the experience behind them.', 2865, 0), (492685, 'Poetry is plucking at the heartstrings, and making music with them.', 30466, 0), (492686, 'I wrote The Green Eye of the Little Yellow God in five hours, but I had it all planned out. It isn''t poetry and it does not pretend to be, but it does what it sets out to do.', 64053, 0), (492687, 'I think of myself as an ambassador of the arts. In my heart of hearts, I know the world would be a more peaceful, tender place if we were more moved by the poetry around us.', 75889, 0), (492688, 'As a rule, men worry more about what they can''t see than about what they can.', 62623, 0), (492689, 'It was pride that changed angels into devils it is humility that makes men as angels. ', 63060, 0), (492690, 'The highest prize in a world of men is the most beautiful woman available on your arm and living there in her heart loyal to you.', 2370, 0), (492691, 'There is nothing noble in being superior to your fellow men. True nobility lies in being superior to your former self.', 110, 0), (492692, 'Wise men don''t need advice. Fools won''t take it.', 1077, 0), (492693, 'Some men see things as they are, and ask why. I dream of things that never were, and ask why not.', 60667, 0), (492694, 'It takes a hero to be one of those men who goes into battle.', 4137, 0), (492695, 'A gentleman is simply a patient wolf.', 68586, 0), (492696, 'It is not titles that honor men, but men that honor titles.', 947, 0), (492697, 'A hero is born among a hundred, a wise man is found among a thousand, but an accomplished one might not be found even among a hundred thousand men.', 51, 0), (492698, 'Let me embrace thee, sour adversity, for wise men say it is the wisest course.', 13, 0), (492699, 'The greatest deception men suffer is from their own opinions.', 1386, 0), (492700, 'I believe in the brotherhood of all men, but I don''t believe in wasting brotherhood on anyone who doesn''t want to practice it with me. Brotherhood is a two-way street.', 1730, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (492701, 'Feminism isn''t about hating men. It''s about challenging the absurd gender distinctions that boys and girls learn from childhood and carry into their adult lives.', 69141, 0), (492702, 'Victory usually goes to the army who has better trained officers and men.', 1026, 0), (492703, 'No man has any natural authority over his fellow men.', 1372, 0), (492704, 'All men''s miseries derive from not being able to sit in a quiet room alone.', 144, 0), (492705, 'Rules are for the obedience of fools and the guidance of wise men.', 75890, 0), (492706, 'Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land.', 1954, 0), (492707, 'Watches are the only jewelry men can wear, unless you''re Mr. T.', 66824, 0), (492708, 'There are three kinds of men. The one that learns by reading. The few who learn by observation. The rest of them have to pee on the electric fence for themselves.', 1122, 0), (492709, 'Men are not prisoners of fate, but only prisoners of their own minds.', 2261, 0), (492710, 'Passion is what gets you through the hardest times that might otherwise make strong men weak, or make you give up.', 404, 0), (492711, 'Gold is good in its place; but loving, brave, patriotic men are better than gold.', 1012, 0), (492712, 'All men''s souls are immortal, but the souls of the righteous are immortal and divine.', 1595, 0), (492713, 'If any civilization is to survive, it is the morality of altruism that men have to reject.', 631, 0), (492714, 'I think women are foolish to pretend they are equal to men they are far superior and always have been. ', 1371, 0), (492715, 'Men go abroad to wonder at the heights of mountains, at the huge waves of the sea, at the long courses of the rivers, at the vast compass of the ocean, at the circular motions of the stars, and they pass by themselves without wondering.', 63060, 0), (492716, 'Those who profess to favor freedom, and yet depreciate agitation, are men who want crops without plowing up the ground.', 7432, 0), (492717, 'We must continue to prove to the world that we can provide a rising standard of living for all men without loss of civil rights or human dignity to any man.', 60667, 0), (492718, 'Two men look out the same prison bars one sees mud and the other stars. ', 9972, 0), (492719, 'It doesn''t take a hero to order men into battle. It takes a hero to be one of those men who goes into battle.', 4137, 0), (492720, 'The hero is one who kindles a great light in the world, who sets up blazing torches in the dark streets of life for men to see by.', 3705, 0), (492721, 'Men lose all the material things they leave behind them in this world, but they carry with them the reward of their charity and the alms they give. For these, they will receive from the Lord the reward and recompense they deserve.', 1681, 0), (492722, 'The Industrial Revolution has two phases: one material, the other social; one concerning the making of things, the other concerning the making of men.', 28619, 0), (492723, 'It does not take a majority to prevail... but rather an irate, tireless minority, keen on setting brushfires of freedom in the minds of men.', 16829, 0), (492724, 'A lawyer with his briefcase can steal more than a hundred men with guns.', 451, 0), (492725, 'Men often oppose a thing merely because they have had no agency in planning it, or because it may have been planned by those whom they dislike.', 16733, 0), (492726, 'The only use of an obstacle is to be overcome. All that an obstacle does with brave men is, not to frighten them, but to challenge them.', 1970, 0), (492727, 'These people are very unskilled in arms... with 50 men they could all be subjected and made to do all that one wished.', 70809, 0), (492728, 'Fire is the test of gold; adversity, of strong men.', 1209, 0), (492729, 'Timid men prefer the calm of despotism to the tempestuous sea of liberty.', 1207, 0), (492730, 'The evil that men do lives after them the good is oft interred with 